Entity-other_property.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'other properties' refers to additional properties that can be defined within the knowledge graph, which may include relationships and attributes that are not explicitly categorized or linked to existing properties, thus complicating the maintenance of disjointness among them.

Entity-existing_property.label: existing properties
Entity-existing_property.description: Existing properties in the context of Wikidata refer to the properties that have already been defined within the Wikidata ontology, which are used to link entities and provide structured data, but may require updates to enhance their connections to external ontologies.

Entity-http__www.wikidata.orgwikispecial.label: https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityData/
Entity-http__www.wikidata.orgwikispecial.description: A web resource that provides structured data about entities in Wikidata, identified by a unique URI.

Entity-class_from_external_ontology.label: classes from external ontologies
Entity-class_from_external_ontology.description: Classes from external ontologies refer to the categorizations or classifications of entities that are defined in ontologies outside of Wikidata's own authoritative namespace, which Wikidata does not utilize for typing its entities.

Entity-the_community.label: the community
Entity-the_community.description: The community refers to the group of editors and contributors who collaboratively build and maintain the Wikidata knowledge graph by adding and managing data without relying on formal ontological frameworks.

Entity-instance_of_relation.label: instance of relation
Entity-instance_of_relation.description: The 'instance of relation' refers to a specific property in Wikidata, denoted as P31, which is used to classify entities by linking them to their corresponding classes within the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-automatic_integration_of_external.label: automatic integration of external data through bots
aliases: automatic integration of external data through bots
Entity-automatic_integration_of_external.description: The term 'automatic integration of external data through bots' refers to the process by which automated software agents, or bots, facilitate the seamless incorporation of data from external knowledge sources into Wikidata, enhancing its content and connectivity, as exemplified by bots like the Citationgraph bot that updates citation information.

mentions.local_name: automatic integration of external data through bots

Entity-wikidata_s_qualified_statement.label: Wikidata's qualified statements
Entity-wikidata_s_qualified_statement.description: Wikidata's qualified statements refer to the enhanced RDF statements in Wikidata that allow for the inclusion of additional contextual or provenance information, akin to reification, thereby enriching the data representation within the knowledge graph.

Entity-result.label: results
Entity-result.description: The 'results' refer to the findings and outcomes derived from the analysis of link types in Wikidata and the testing of hypotheses regarding its role in the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-3955_class_link.label: 3,955 class links
Entity-3955_class_link.description: The term '3,955 class links' refers to the total number of defined links in Wikidata that connect its classes to external ontologies or datasets within the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-recent_addition.label: recent additions
Entity-recent_addition.description: The term 'recent additions' refers to newly introduced properties in the Wikidata ontology that are specifically designed to facilitate links to external ontologies or allow the use of external URIs.

Entity-number.label: number
Entity-number.description: The mention 'number' refers to the quantitative measure of links from entities in Wikidata to other knowledge graphs, specifically indicating the total count of such links.

Entity-linked_open_data.label: Linked Open Data
Entity-linked_open_data.description: Linked Open Data refers to a method of publishing structured data on the web in a way that allows it to be interlinked and become more useful through semantic connections.

Entity-problem.label: problems
Entity-problem.description: The term 'problems' refers to the semantic errors or inconsistencies that arise within the Wikidata knowledge graph due to its community-driven, bottom-up construction approach.

Entity-external_uris.label: external URIs
Entity-external_uris.description: External URIs refer to Uniform Resource Identifiers that are sourced from outside the Wikidata namespace, used to link to classes and properties defined in other ontologies or datasets within the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-95_million_entity.label: 95 million entities
Entity-95_million_entity.description: The mention '95 million entities' refers to the total number of distinct items or concepts represented within the Wikidata knowledge graph, which serves as a multilingual repository of structured data.

Entity-resource.label: resources
Entity-resource.description: In this context, 'resources' refers to various external entities linked from Wikidata that do not conform to the RDF format, indicating a distinction between different types of linked data.

Entity-visibility.label: visibility
Entity-visibility.description: In this context, 'visibility' refers to the enhanced discoverability of external datasets achieved through the creation of outgoing links from Wikidata.

Entity-property_link_ratio.label: property link ratio
Entity-property_link_ratio.description: The property link ratio is a metric that quantifies the average number of links to external ontologies per property in Wikidata, highlighting the interconnectedness of its properties with other knowledge graphs.

Entity-wiki_page_(1).label: wiki pages
Entity-wiki_page_(1).description: Wiki pages refer to the web pages that describe entities within the Wikidata knowledge graph, utilizing a predefined schema to define statements and relationships about those entities.

Entity-each_unique_entity.label: each unique entity
Entity-each_unique_entity.description: Each unique entity refers to an individual defined within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which is associated with a subgraph containing additional entities that provide detailed information and qualifiers about that individual.

Entity-exact_match_relation.label: exact match relation
Entity-exact_match_relation.description: The 'exact match relation' in Wikidata refers to a specific type of link that connects a Wikidata entity to an authoritative representation of the same entity in an external dataset, facilitating interoperability within the Linked Open Data ecosystem.

Entity-approach_(1).label: approaches
Entity-approach_(1).description: In the context of this paper, 'approaches' refers to various methodologies and frameworks used to assess the quality and interlinking of linked data, particularly in relation to Wikidata.

Entity-world.label: world
Entity-world.description: In this context, 'world' refers to the various entities and concepts that exist within the knowledge graph of Wikidata, which are represented by a rich set of statements added by the community.

Entity-likeness_relation.label: likeness relations
Entity-likeness_relation.description: Likeness relations refer to the equivalence or weaker forms of relationships established by Wikidata between its unique individuals and entities defined in other authoritative namespaces, facilitating connections in the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-link_type.label: link types
Entity-link_type.description: Link types refer to the classifications of connections between entities in the Wikidata data model, specifically distinguishing between Ontology (TBox) Links and Instance (ABox) Links, which are further categorized into various subtypes such as class links, instance typing links, property links, and instance role links.

Entity-knowledge_about_thing.label: knowledge about things
Entity-knowledge_about_thing.description: The phrase 'knowledge about things' refers to the understanding and representation of entities, their classifications, and the relationships between them as defined within the context of the RDF model, specifically in relation to the ontological structure of Wikidata.

Entity-quality_issue.label: quality issues
Entity-quality_issue.description: Quality issues refer to the semantic errors or inconsistencies present in the knowledge graph of Wikidata, particularly concerning the accuracy and evolution of its data and its schema-level relations to other ontologies.

Entity-a_more_broadly_accepted_web_ontol.label: a more broadly accepted Web ontology
aliases: a more broadly accepted Web ontology
Entity-a_more_broadly_accepted_web_ontol.description: A more broadly accepted Web ontology refers to a collaborative and evolving framework for defining and linking concepts on the Web, which aims to integrate various domain-specific and upper-level ontologies into a cohesive structure that enhances interoperability and semantic understanding across different knowledge graphs.

mentions.local_name: a more broadly accepted Web ontology

Entity-link_to_wikipedia.label: links to Wikipedia
Entity-link_to_wikipedia.description: The term 'links to Wikipedia' refers to the connections established from entities in Wikidata to corresponding entries in Wikipedia, which serve as external references but do not conform to the RDF resource format.

Entity-quality_analysis_of_wikidata.label: quality analysis of Wikidata
Entity-quality_analysis_of_wikidata.description: The quality analysis of Wikidata refers to the systematic evaluation of the accuracy, completeness, and reliability of the data contained within the Wikidata knowledge base.

Entity-2012.description: The mention '2012' refers to the year when Wikidata was initiated as a knowledge graph, designed to be collaboratively built by editors and automated bots.

Entity-object.label: object
Entity-object.description: In the context of the paper, 'object' refers to a specific entity within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that can appear in the subject or object position of RDF triples, which are used to represent relationships and properties in linked data.

Entity-completeness_of_it_relation.label: completeness of its relations
Entity-completeness_of_it_relation.description: The 'completeness of its relations' refers to a data quality criterion that evaluates how thoroughly the relationships between entities in Wikidata are represented and linked to other knowledge graphs.

Entity-specific_property.label: specific properties
Entity-specific_property.description: The term 'specific properties' refers to particular attributes defined within the Wikidata ontology that are intended to establish links to external properties in the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-it_alignment_property.label: its alignment properties
Entity-it_alignment_property.description: The term 'its alignment properties' refers to the characteristics and quality aspects of how Wikidata's data structures and semantics correspond and integrate with established standards and frameworks such as RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org.

Entity-other_work.label: Other work
Entity-other_work.description: Other work refers to various research studies and analyses that focus on interlinking in linked data and quality assessments related to linked data, but do not specifically address the interlinking and centrality of Wikidata within the Linked Open Data ecosystem.

Entity-unique_predicate.label: unique predicates
Entity-unique_predicate.description: Unique predicates in Wikidata refer to the distinct properties or attributes that can be assigned to entities within the knowledge graph, totaling 38,867 as per the analysis presented in the paper.

Entity-entity.label: entity
Entity-entity.description: In Wikidata, 'entity' refers to the top-level class (Q35120) that encompasses all items, including both classes and instances, serving as a foundational category in the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-terminological_entity.label: terminological entities
Entity-terminological_entity.description: Terminological entities in Wikidata refer to the classes and properties that are defined within its own authoritative namespace, which are used to represent and categorize the various entities in the knowledge graph.

Entity-external_subproperty.label: external subproperty
Entity-external_subproperty.description: The 'external subproperty' (P2236) in Wikidata is a property used to establish a hierarchical relationship between properties in Wikidata and those in external vocabularies, functioning similarly to the rdfs:subPropertyOf relation.

Entity-18_entity.label: 18 entities
Entity-18_entity.description: The term '18 entities' refers to the average number of additional entities created as part of the subgraph for each unique entity in Wikidata, which redirect to the target entity through the Linked Data API.

Entity-triple.label: triples
Entity-triple.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'triples' refer to the structured statements that consist of subject-predicate-object combinations used to represent relationships and attributes of entities within the knowledge graph.

Entity-wikidata_editor.label: Wikidata editors
Entity-wikidata_editor.description: Wikidata editors are individuals or groups who contribute to and manage the content of Wikidata, a collaborative knowledge base that serves as a central storage for structured data used by Wikimedia projects.

Entity-the_attribute_that_can_be_assigne.label: the attributes that can be assigned to those entities
aliases: the attributes that can be assigned to those entities
Entity-the_attribute_that_can_be_assigne.description: The attributes that can be assigned to entities in Wikidata refer to the limited set of properties or characteristics that describe and define the unique individuals within the knowledge graph.

mentions.local_name: the attributes that can be assigned to those entities

Entity-link_from_an_ontology_to_other_on.label: links from an ontology to other ontologies
aliases: links from an ontology to other ontologies
Entity-link_from_an_ontology_to_other_on.description: Links from an ontology to other ontologies refer to the connections established between different ontologies, typically implemented through mechanisms such as import statements or URI reuse, to enhance interoperability and facilitate the integration of knowledge across diverse data sources.

mentions.local_name: links from an ontology to other ontologies

Entity-wdt__p2888.label: wdt:P2888
Entity-wdt__p2888.description: wdt:P2888 is a Wikidata property that denotes an exact match between a Wikidata entity and an external identifier, specifically used to link to the Human Disease Ontology.

Entity-incoherent_meta-modeling_of_class.label: incoherent meta-modeling of classes/instances
Entity-incoherent_meta-modeling_of_class.description: Incoherent meta-modeling of classes/instances refers to the semantic errors and inconsistencies that arise in the community-driven construction of the Wikidata knowledge graph, where the informal and flexible nature of its meta-model leads to a lack of logical consistency in the representation of classes and instances.

Entity-it_own_namespace.label: its own namespace
Entity-it_own_namespace.description: The term 'its own namespace' refers to the authoritative and self-contained domain within which a knowledge graph, such as Wikidata, defines its classes and properties, allowing it to maintain semantic consistency and independence from external ontologies.

Entity-upper-level_or_domain_ontology.label: upper-level or domain ontologies
Entity-upper-level_or_domain_ontology.description: Upper-level or domain ontologies refer to structured frameworks that provide a formal representation of knowledge, defining the categories, properties, and relations of concepts within a specific domain or across multiple domains, often used to enhance semantic interoperability in knowledge graphs like Wikidata.

Entity-class_uri.label: class URI
Entity-class_uri.description: The term 'class URI' refers to a specific type of Uniform Resource Identifier that denotes a class within the context of the Wikidata knowledge graph, used to identify and link to external ontological classes in the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-framework.label: framework
Entity-framework.description: The 'framework' refers to a proposed methodology for evaluating the quality of the Wikidata ontology as it evolves, specifically in relation to the roles of different users.

Entity-the_remainder_of_this_paper.label: The remainder of this paper
Entity-the_remainder_of_this_paper.description: The remainder of this paper refers to the subsequent sections that outline the structure and content of the analysis, including discussions on ontology in Wikidata, methodology for analyzing link types, results of the analysis, related work, and conclusions.

Entity-our_proposed_mapping.label: our proposed mapping
Entity-our_proposed_mapping.description: Our proposed mapping refers to a specific interpretation of the evolving meta-model in Wikidata, designed to provide formal semantics for link analysis between entities, while acknowledging the community's intentional lack of a definitive mapping to maintain flexibility in ontological commitments.

Entity-these_relation.label: these relations
Entity-these_relation.description: These relations refer to the external subproperty and superproperty links that should be introduced in Wikidata to enhance the connectivity of its properties with external ontologies.

Entity-the_lack_of_such_link.label: the lack of such links
Entity-the_lack_of_such_link.description: The lack of such links refers to the insufficient connections between entities defined in Wikidata and external entities in the Linked Open Data ecosystem, which may suggest that these entities are either not represented in the ecosystem or are not being linked appropriately.

Entity-user.label: users
Entity-user.description: The term 'users' refers to individuals who contribute to the collaborative development and modeling of entities within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-hierarchy.label: hierarchies
Entity-hierarchy.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'hierarchies' refers to the structured relationships that define class memberships and taxonomic relations among entities, particularly through properties like 'subclass of' and 'subproperty of' that establish hierarchical connections within the knowledge graph.

Entity-we.label: We
Entity-we.description: In this context, 'We' refers to the authors of the paper who are conducting research to adapt and apply existing definitions of ontology and instance links to the Wikidata data model.

Entity-property_for_property.label: properties for properties
Entity-property_for_property.description: The term 'properties for properties' refers to specific terminological properties defined within the Wikidata ontology that describe the relationships and characteristics of other properties in the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-linked_data.label: Linked Data
Entity-linked_data.description: Linked Data is a method of publishing structured data on the web in a way that allows it to be interlinked and become more useful through semantic connections.

Entity-adapted_correspondence.label: adapted correspondences
Entity-adapted_correspondence.description: Adapted correspondences refer to the reformulated definitions and mappings of link types between the Wikidata data model and the RDFS/OWL semantics, which are operationalized through SPARQL queries to analyze and retrieve various types of links in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-the_majority_of_link.label: The majority of links
Entity-the_majority_of_link.description: The majority of links refers to the links in Wikidata that connect to resources which are not represented as RDF (Resource Description Framework) entities.

Entity-an_overview_and_statistic_of_vari.label: an overview and statistics of various multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties
aliases: an overview and statistics of various multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties
Entity-an_overview_and_statistic_of_vari.description: The term refers to the WDProp tool, which offers users a comprehensive summary and statistical data regarding the multi-language features of Wikidata properties, including their labels, descriptions, and aliases.

mentions.local_name: an overview and statistics of various multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties

Entity-a_bottom-up_development.label: a bottom-up development
Entity-a_bottom-up_development.description: A bottom-up development refers to the collaborative and organic process by which the vocabulary and structure of Wikidata are constructed by its community of users, potentially leading to a more widely accepted ontology for the Web.

Entity-incoherent_meta-modeling.label: incoherent meta-modeling
Entity-incoherent_meta-modeling.description: Incoherent meta-modeling refers to the semantic errors or inconsistencies that arise in the community-developed ontology of Wikidata, particularly in the representation of classes and instances due to its flexible, bottom-up construction approach.

Entity-wikiba.seontology.label: wikiba.se/ontology
Entity-wikiba.seontology.description: wikiba.se/ontology refers to the minimal predefined schema used by Wikidata to describe the wiki pages of entities, including the definition of what constitutes a statement for an entity.

Entity-survey.label: survey
Entity-survey.description: The mention 'survey' refers to a comprehensive research study conducted by Färber et al. that evaluates various open knowledge graphs (KGs), with a particular focus on Wikidata.

Entity-the_431_from_above.label: the 431 from above
Entity-the_431_from_above.description: The 431 from above refers to a collection of 431 Linked Datasets that are part of a corpus used for analyzing links in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-the_linked_data_ecosystem.label: the Linked Data ecosystem
Entity-the_linked_data_ecosystem.description: The Linked Data ecosystem refers to a framework and set of technologies that enable the interlinking and sharing of structured data across the web using standard protocols and formats, facilitating data integration and interoperability.

Entity-drawback.label: drawbacks
Entity-drawback.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'drawbacks' refers to the semantic errors or inconsistencies that arise from its flexible, community-driven approach to knowledge graph construction, particularly issues related to incoherent meta-modeling of classes and instances.

Entity-the_number_of_class_link.label: the number of class links
Entity-the_number_of_class_link.description: The number of class links refers to the total count of defined connections between classes in Wikidata and external ontologies or datasets, which is currently limited to 3,955 links despite the existence of over 2.5 million classes.

Entity-relation_similar_to_external_subp.label: relation similar to 'external subproperty'
Entity-relation_similar_to_external_subp.description: The term 'relation similar to external subproperty' refers to a proposed relational framework in Wikidata that would facilitate the definition of external subclass relationships, thereby enhancing the connectivity of Wikidata with external ontologies and knowledge graphs.

Entity-wikidata_rdf_corpus.label: Wikidata RDF corpus
Entity-wikidata_rdf_corpus.description: The Wikidata RDF corpus is a structured dataset that contains information from Wikidata represented in the Resource Description Framework (RDF) format, enabling semantic web applications and data integration.

Entity-entity_defined_in_it_authoritativ.label: entities defined in its authoritative namespace
aliases: entities defined in other authoritative namespaces
entities defined within the Wikidata authoritative namespace
entities defined in its authoritative namespace
Entity-entity_defined_in_it_authoritativ.description: The phrase 'entities defined in its authoritative namespace' refers to the unique entities, classes, and properties that are created and maintained within the Wikidata knowledge graph, which are not reliant on external ontologies for their definitions.

mentions.local_name: entities defined in its authoritative namespace
entities defined within the Wikidata authoritative namespace
entities defined in other authoritative namespaces

Entity-reason_for_this.label: reasons for this
Entity-reason_for_this.description: The term 'reasons for this' refers to the factors or explanations identified in the paper that account for the limited extent of linking between Wikidata and other knowledge graphs.

Entity-8.6.description: The term '8.6' refers to the ratio of links to entities in the Linked Open Data ecosystem, indicating a higher interconnectedness compared to the ratio of links to entities in Wikidata, which is 1.94.

Entity-instance_of__p31_.label: instance of (P31)
Entity-instance_of__p31_.description: A property in Wikidata that indicates the relationship between an item and its class or type.

Entity-external_property.label: external properties
Entity-external_property.description: The term 'external properties' refers to properties in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that are utilized in various relationships or definitions but are not explicitly declared as properties within Wikidata itself.

Entity-multi-language_aspect_of_wikidata.label: multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties
Entity-multi-language_aspect_of_wikidata.description: The multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties refer to the various linguistic features associated with Wikidata properties, including the different labels, descriptions, and aliases available in multiple languages, which are analyzed and presented through the WDProp tool.

Entity-this_liberty.label: This liberty
Entity-this_liberty.description: This liberty refers to the flexibility and freedom that the Wikidata community has in rapidly extending the knowledge graph by adding a diverse set of statements about entities without strict adherence to logical consistency, which can lead to semantic errors or inconsistencies.

Entity-linked_open_vocabulary.label: Linked Open Vocabularies
Entity-linked_open_vocabulary.description: Linked Open Vocabularies is a collection of structured vocabularies that are published as Linked Data, facilitating interoperability and reuse of data across different domains.

Entity-class_and_property_in_wikidata.label: classes and properties in Wikidata
Entity-class_and_property_in_wikidata.description: Classes and properties in Wikidata refer to the structured data elements that define the types of items and their relationships within the Wikidata knowledge base.

Entity-open_kg.label: open KGs
Entity-open_kg.description: Open KGs refer to publicly accessible knowledge graphs that provide structured information and data for various applications, enabling users to query and utilize the knowledge contained within them.

Entity-web.label: Web
Entity-web.description: The Web refers to the global information system that enables the interconnection and access of data and resources through the internet, particularly in the context of open knowledge graphs like Wikidata.

Entity-anyone_who_owns_a_dataset.label: anyone who owns a dataset
Entity-anyone_who_owns_a_dataset.description: The term 'anyone who owns a dataset' refers to individuals or entities that possess a dataset and have the capability to create outgoing links from the Wikidata knowledge graph to their dataset, thereby enhancing its visibility and discoverability within the Linked Open Data ecosystem.

Entity-wikidata_namespace_uri.label: Wikidata namespace URI
Entity-wikidata_namespace_uri.description: The Wikidata namespace URI is a specific Uniform Resource Identifier that designates the namespace used for entities within the Wikidata knowledge base.

Entity-hypothesis_h4.2.label: hypothesis H4.2
Entity-hypothesis_h4.2.description: Hypothesis H4.2 refers to a research proposition that aims to evaluate the nature of instance links in Wikidata by analyzing a sample of target URIs to determine whether they point to RDF resources.

Entity-subclass_of_relation.label: subclass of relation
Entity-subclass_of_relation.description: The term 'subclass of relation' refers to a type of ontological link that indicates a hierarchical relationship where one class is defined as a more specific category under another class within the context of the Wikidata data model.

Entity-entity_in_the_world.label: entities in the world
Entity-entity_in_the_world.description: The term 'entities in the world' refers to the various individuals, classes, and properties represented within the Wikidata knowledge graph, which are defined and described by the community through a flexible, bottom-up approach.

Entity-section_2.label: Section 2
Entity-section_2.description: Section 2 refers to the part of the paper where the authors discuss the ontology in Wikidata and present their mapping semantics between the Wikidata meta-model and RDFS/OWL.

Entity-label.label: labels
Entity-label.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'labels' refer to the multi-language textual identifiers assigned to entities that help users understand and recognize them across different languages.

Entity-it_many_editor.label: its many editors
Entity-it_many_editor.description: The term 'its many editors' refers to the diverse community of contributors who collaboratively build and maintain the Wikidata knowledge graph, enhancing its content and structure through their collective expertise and input.

Entity-this_number.label: this number
Entity-this_number.description: This number refers to the total count of links from entities in Wikidata to Wikipedia, indicating the extent of connectivity between these two knowledge sources.

Entity-wikidata_editor_community.label: Wikidata editor community
Entity-wikidata_editor_community.description: The Wikidata editor community is a collective of individuals who contribute to and maintain the Wikidata knowledge base by editing, adding, and improving data entries.

Entity-2794_ontology.label: 2,794 ontologies
Entity-2794_ontology.description: The term '2,794 ontologies' refers to the total number of ontologies that were registered in the prefix.cc repository as of August 2021, which are utilized in the analysis of links within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-first_hypothesis.label: first hypothesis
Entity-first_hypothesis.description: The 'first hypothesis' refers to the assertion that Wikidata defines the vast majority of its terminological entities and properties within its own authoritative namespace, which is tested to evaluate its role as a central hub for Linked Data.

Entity-individual_defined_in_wikidata.label: individuals defined in Wikidata
Entity-individual_defined_in_wikidata.description: Individuals defined in Wikidata refer to unique entities or persons that are cataloged within the Wikidata knowledge base, each represented by a specific identifier and associated with various properties and relationships.

Entity-citationgraph_bot.label: Citationgraph bot
Entity-citationgraph_bot.description: The Citationgraph bot is an automated tool used in Wikidata to update citation numbers of academic works by integrating external data.

Entity-discussion.label: discussions
Entity-discussion.description: The term 'discussions' refers to the collaborative dialogues among Wikidata editors aimed at resolving semantic errors and inconsistencies within the knowledge graph.

Entity-auto-generated_link.label: auto-generated links
Entity-auto-generated_link.description: Auto-generated links refer to automatically created connections in Wikidata that classify entities as specific types, such as schema:Dataset and schema:Article, without user intervention.

Entity-number_of_class_link.label: number of Class Links
Entity-number_of_class_link.description: The 'number of Class Links' refers to the total count of external class URIs that are utilized in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, as determined by their occurrence in triples within the dataset.

Entity-class.label: class
Entity-class.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'class' refers to the top-level ontology element that categorizes items, specifically identified as class (Q16889133), which is a subclass of the broader entity class (Q35120).

Entity-the_object_uri.label: the object URI
Entity-the_object_uri.description: The object URI refers to a unique identifier used in the context of the Wikidata Knowledge Graph to denote an external resource or entity that is linked to a subject in a triple, specifically ensuring that it does not belong to the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-an_assessment_of_wikidata.label: an assessment of Wikidata
Entity-an_assessment_of_wikidata.description: An assessment of Wikidata refers to an evaluation conducted by Freire and Isaac that focuses on the quality of machine interpretation of Wikidata's alignment properties with various semantic web standards such as RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org.

Entity-linked_data_ecosystem.label: Linked Data ecosystem
Entity-linked_data_ecosystem.description: The Linked Data ecosystem refers to a framework and set of technologies that enable the interlinking and sharing of structured data across the web using standard protocols and formats, facilitating the creation of a network of connected data sources.

Entity-unique_individual.label: unique individuals
Entity-unique_individual.description: The term 'unique individuals' refers to distinct entities defined within the Wikidata authoritative namespace that are linked to corresponding entities in other authoritative namespaces, highlighting their role in establishing equivalence or likeness relations in the context of Linked Data.

Entity-hypothesis_h2.2.label: hypothesis H2.2
Entity-hypothesis_h2.2.description: Hypothesis H2.2 refers to the research claim that Wikidata includes many more property links per property than other datasets, which was ultimately rejected based on the analysis presented in the paper.

Entity-173_million_instance_typing_link.label: 173 million instance typing links
Entity-173_million_instance_typing_link.description: The '173 million instance typing links' refers to the auto-generated links in Wikidata that classify entities using the rdf:type relation, primarily designating them as schema:Dataset and schema:Article.

Entity-target_resource.label: target resources
Entity-target_resource.description: The term 'target resources' refers to the external entities linked from Wikidata that are not represented as RDF resources, specifically highlighting that these links often point to Wikipedia entries rather than RDF-compliant data.

Entity-class_defined_within_wikidata.label: classes defined within Wikidata
Entity-class_defined_within_wikidata.description: Classes defined within Wikidata refer to the categories or types of entities that are organized and structured within the Wikidata knowledge base, allowing for the classification and representation of various concepts and items.

Entity-property_defined_within_wikidata.label: properties defined within Wikidata
Entity-property_defined_within_wikidata.description: Properties defined within Wikidata are specific attributes or characteristics that can be used to describe items in the Wikidata knowledge base, facilitating structured data representation and retrieval.

Entity-axiomatic_theory_for_multi-level_.label: axiomatic theory for multi-level modeling
aliases: An axiomatic theory for multi-level modeling
Entity-axiomatic_theory_for_multi-level_.description: The axiomatic theory for multi-level modeling is a theoretical framework employed to analyze the content of Wikidata, specifically aimed at identifying issues related to classification and taxonomic statements within the knowledge graph.

mentions.local_name: An axiomatic theory for multi-level modeling

Entity-liberty.label: liberty
Entity-liberty.description: In this context, 'liberty' refers to the freedom and flexibility that the community of editors in Wikidata has to rapidly extend the knowledge graph by adding a diverse set of statements about entities, which, while beneficial, can lead to semantic errors and inconsistencies.

Entity-description.label: descriptions
Entity-description.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'descriptions' refer to the textual explanations or definitions associated with entities that provide additional context and information about them in multiple languages.

Entity-2.5_million_class.label: 2.5 million classes
Entity-2.5_million_class.description: The term '2.5 million classes' refers to the total number of unique class URIs defined in Wikidata, which are classified as undeclared according to RDFS/OWL semantics, highlighting the extensive but underutilized class structure within this open knowledge graph.

Entity-modelling_choice.label: modelling choices
Entity-modelling_choice.description: The term 'modelling choices' refers to the various decisions made by users in Wikidata regarding the classification and hierarchy of entities, which can lead to inconsistencies in the representation of subclasses and instances within the knowledge graph.

Entity-linked_open_data_corpus.label: Linked Open Data corpus
aliases: the Linked Open Data (LOD) dataset corpus
Entity-linked_open_data_corpus.description: The Linked Open Data corpus is a collection of datasets that are interlinked and accessible on the web, enabling the integration and sharing of structured data across different domains.

mentions.local_name: the Linked Open Data (LOD) dataset corpus

Entity-different_expertise.label: different expertise
Entity-different_expertise.description: Different expertise refers to the diverse knowledge and skills possessed by the community of users contributing to Wikidata, which enhances its functionality and connections to various data sources.

Entity-the_ontology.label: the ontology
Entity-the_ontology.description: The ontology refers to a formal representation of a set of concepts within a domain, including the relationships between those concepts, which is essential for enabling shared understanding and interoperability among different datasets in the context of the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-external_uri.label: external URI
Entity-external_uri.description: An external URI refers to a Uniform Resource Identifier that is sourced from a namespace outside of the Wikidata knowledge graph, which cannot be directly linked to instances within Wikidata due to limitations in the Wikibase platform.

Entity-ontology__tbox__link.label: Ontology (TBox) Links
Entity-ontology__tbox__link.description: Ontology (TBox) Links refer to the connections or relationships defined within the TBox of an ontology, which encapsulate the conceptual framework and the types of entities and their properties in a knowledge representation system.

Entity-top-ranked_instance.label: top-ranked instance
Entity-top-ranked_instance.description: The 'top-ranked instance' refers to the highest-priority or most significant entities identified in the analysis of links from Wikidata to external datasets and ontologies.

Entity-6379_class_per_dataset.label: 6,379 classes per dataset
Entity-6379_class_per_dataset.description: The term '6,379 classes per dataset' refers to the average number of distinct classes utilized in various datasets within the Linked Open Vocabularies corpus, highlighting a comparative metric against the significantly larger number of classes defined in Wikidata.

Entity-pillai_et_al_..label: Pillai et al.
Entity-pillai_et_al_..description: Pillai et al. refers to a group of researchers who conducted a comparative analysis of Wikidata and other knowledge graphs, focusing on data quality criteria such as completeness of relations, timeliness, and accessibility.

Entity-high-quality_machine_interpretati.label: high-quality machine interpretation
Entity-high-quality_machine_interpretati.description: High-quality machine interpretation refers to the evaluation and analysis of Wikidata's alignment properties with various semantic web standards such as RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org, ensuring that the data can be accurately understood and utilized by machines.

Entity-dataset_corpus.label: dataset corpus
Entity-dataset_corpus.description: The dataset corpus refers to a collection of 431 Linked Datasets, including those from the LODCloud and LODLaundromat, encoded in HDT format, totaling approximately 17.8 billion triples and used for analyzing links in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-authoritative_namespace_of_the_kn.label: authoritative namespace of the knowledge graph
aliases: authoritative namespace of the knowledge graph
Entity-authoritative_namespace_of_the_kn.description: The 'authoritative namespace of the knowledge graph' refers to the specific domain within Wikidata where class URIs are officially defined and recognized, as opposed to those that are borrowed from external sources.

mentions.local_name: authoritative namespace of the knowledge graph

Entity-data_.label: data:
Entity-data_.description: The mention 'data:' refers to a prefix used in the context of the Wikidata data model to denote a specific namespace associated with external datasets.

Entity-that_target_entity.label: that target entity
Entity-that_target_entity.description: The term 'that target entity' refers to a specific unique entity within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which is linked to various qualified statements and subgraphs that provide additional context and attributes about it.

Entity-wikidata_user_role.label: Wikidata user roles
Entity-wikidata_user_role.description: Wikidata user roles refer to the various permissions and responsibilities assigned to users within the Wikidata platform, which influence their ability to edit, manage, and contribute to the collaborative knowledge base.

Entity-this_phenomenon.label: this phenomenon
Entity-this_phenomenon.description: This phenomenon refers to the observation that a knowledge graph, such as DBpedia, defines the vast majority of its terminological entities and properties within its own authoritative namespace, which enhances its robustness and reliability as a central hub for Linked Data.

Entity-many_other_knowledge_graph.label: many other knowledge graphs
Entity-many_other_knowledge_graph.description: The term 'many other knowledge graphs' refers to various knowledge graphs that maintain a clear distinction between TBox (terminological box) and ABox (assertional box) axioms, unlike Wikidata, which allows instances to also be defined as classes.

Entity-link_target.label: link target
Entity-link_target.description: The term 'link target' refers to entities within a knowledge graph (KG) that serve as reliable references for other KGs, particularly when these entities are defined within the KG's own namespace, thus ensuring stability against changes in external ontologies.

Entity-3268021_such_link.label: 3,268,021 such links
Entity-3268021_such_link.description: 3,268,021 such links refers to the number of instance links in Wikidata that utilize the exact match relation to connect unique individuals defined in namespaces other than the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-wd_.label: wd:
Entity-wd_.description: The mention 'wd:' refers to the prefix used in Wikidata to denote URIs within its own namespace, specifically for entities and properties defined in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-schema_.label: schema:
Entity-schema_.description: The mention 'schema:' refers to the prefix used to denote the namespace associated with the schema.org vocabulary, which is utilized in the context of linking data types and properties in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-external_superproperty.label: external superproperty
Entity-external_superproperty.description: The external superproperty is a property in Wikidata (identified by P2235) that is used to establish a hierarchical relationship indicating that a property in Wikidata is a superproperty of a property defined in an external namespace.

Entity-knowledge_graph.label: knowledge graphs
Entity-knowledge_graph.description: Knowledge graphs are structured representations of information that use graph-based models to connect and organize data, enabling the integration and retrieval of knowledge across various domains.

Entity-unique_class_defined_in_wikidata.label: unique classes defined in Wikidata
Entity-unique_class_defined_in_wikidata.description: The 'unique classes defined in Wikidata' refers to the 2,522,595 class URIs that are created within the Wikidata knowledge graph but are not formally declared using rdf:type relations, making them undeclared according to RDFS/OWL semantics.

Entity-our_last_hypothesis.label: our last hypothesis
Entity-our_last_hypothesis.description: The term 'our last hypothesis' refers to the hypothesis (H5) that tests the extent to which Wikidata claims to be the only authoritative source for its entities, suggesting that a central hub for Linked Data should primarily provide persistent identities while linking to external authoritative sources.

Entity-additional_information.label: additional information
Entity-additional_information.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'additional information' refers to supplementary data that can be appended to statements to provide context or provenance, enhancing the expressiveness and detail of the information represented in the knowledge graph.

Entity-each_individual_reused.label: each individual reused
Entity-each_individual_reused.description: The term 'each individual reused' refers to unique entities from non-authoritative namespace URIs that are incorporated into the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, specifically in the context of instance links where these entities are utilized in the object position of triples.

Entity-attribute.label: attributes
Entity-attribute.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'attributes' refer to the limited set of properties or characteristics that can be assigned to the potentially infinite number of entities within the knowledge graph.

Entity-these_instance.label: These instances
Entity-these_instance.description: These instances refer to specific entities in Wikidata that are classified under a particular class through the 'instance of' (P31) relation, illustrating the relationship between individual items and their corresponding classes within the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-class_link_per_class.label: class links per class
Entity-class_link_per_class.description: The term 'class links per class' refers to a metric that quantifies the average number of external class links associated with each class in a knowledge graph, specifically highlighting the low ratio of such links in Wikidata compared to other datasets.

Entity-persistent_identity.label: persistent identity
Entity-persistent_identity.description: The term 'persistent identity' refers to the role of a knowledge graph, such as Wikidata, in providing a stable and consistent identifier for an entity that links to its authoritative external source, rather than being the primary source of information about that entity.

Entity-89_million_unique_individual.label: 89 million unique individuals
Entity-89_million_unique_individual.description: The mention '89 million unique individuals' refers to the total number of distinct entities defined within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which are categorized using its own ontology.

Entity-weaker_form_of_likeness_relation.label: weaker forms of likeness relations
aliases: equivalence or weaker forms of likeness relations
equivalence or some weaker forms of likeness relations
Entity-weaker_form_of_likeness_relation.description: Weaker forms of likeness relations refer to the types of connections between entities in Wikidata and external datasets that indicate similarity or partial equivalence, but do not assert full equivalence, thereby highlighting the need for more nuanced linking in the Linked Open Data ecosystem.

mentions.local_name: equivalence or some weaker forms of likeness relations
equivalence or weaker forms of likeness relations

Entity-domain_entitiesrelations.label: domain entities/relations
Entity-domain_entitiesrelations.description: In the context of knowledge graphs, 'domain entities/relations' refer to the specific entities and relationships defined within a particular ontology or namespace that describe the properties and classes relevant to that domain, as opposed to using external or standard ontological frameworks like RDFS/OWL.

Entity-dsw_d.label: dsW D
Entity-dsw_d.description: dsW D refers to the dataset representing the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which includes authoritative namespaces for entities and properties defined within Wikidata.

Entity-a_similar_process.label: a similar process
Entity-a_similar_process.description: The term 'a similar process' refers to the methodology employed in the analysis of Property Links in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which involves following a defined set of steps to retrieve and evaluate external properties linked to the dataset.

Entity-instance_of.label: instances of
Entity-instance_of.description: The term 'instances of' in the context of Wikidata refers to specific entities that are categorized under a class, indicating that they belong to that class within the hierarchical structure of the knowledge graph.

Entity-external_identifier_for_entity.label: external identifiers for entities
Entity-external_identifier_for_entity.description: External identifiers for entities refer to unique identifiers used to link and integrate data from various external sources into Wikidata, such as ORCID for academics, DOIs for digital objects, and Ensembl identifiers for genes.

Entity-wikipedia_entity.label: Wikipedia entity
Entity-wikipedia_entity.description: A Wikipedia entity refers to a specific item or concept represented within the Wikipedia platform, often linked to corresponding data in Wikidata, serving as a resource for information.

Entity-all_triple_in_the_dataset.label: all triples in the dataset
Entity-all_triple_in_the_dataset.description: The term 'all triples in the dataset' refers to the complete set of RDF triples contained within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which includes all subject-predicate-object statements that represent relationships and attributes of entities defined in Wikidata.

Entity-such_a_mapping.label: such a mapping
Entity-such_a_mapping.description: The term 'such a mapping' refers to a proposed interpretation of the evolving meta-model in Wikidata that aims to provide formal semantics for link analysis between entities, while acknowledging that the community intentionally does not establish a definitive mapping to avoid strong formal ontological commitments.

Entity-p2235.label: P2235
Entity-p2235.description: P2235 refers to the Wikidata property 'external superproperty', which is used to link properties in Wikidata to their corresponding superproperties in external vocabularies.

Entity-superproperty.label: superproperty
Entity-superproperty.description: The term 'superproperty' refers to a specific type of property in the Wikidata ontology that is used to establish hierarchical relationships between properties, indicating that one property is a broader or more general version of another.

Entity-table_1.label: Table 1
Entity-table_1.description: Table 1 presents the definitions and classifications of different link types in the Wikidata data model, specifically detailing the operationalized SPARQL queries that correspond to ontology and instance links.

Entity-statement_about_entity.label: statements about entities
Entity-statement_about_entity.description: The phrase 'statements about entities' refers to the assertions or declarations made within the Wikidata knowledge graph that describe various characteristics, relationships, and properties of entities represented in that graph.

Entity-unique_entity.label: unique entities
Entity-unique_entity.description: The term 'unique entities' refers to the distinct items or concepts defined within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which, as of March 2021, numbered 73 million.

Entity-logical_consistency.label: logical consistency
Entity-logical_consistency.description: Logical consistency refers to the adherence to coherent and non-contradictory relationships among statements and entities within a knowledge graph, which is often less stringent in community-driven models like Wikidata compared to formal ontological frameworks such as RDFS and OWL.

Entity-user_interface_of_wikibase.label: user interface of Wikibase
Entity-user_interface_of_wikibase.description: The user interface of Wikibase refers to the graphical and interactive components of the Wikibase software platform that facilitate user engagement and editing of structured data within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-hypothesis_5.label: Hypothesis 5
Entity-hypothesis_5.description: Hypothesis 5 refers to the research claim that a significant number of instance links in Wikidata utilize equivalence or likeness relations, which was ultimately rejected based on the analysis of the data.

Entity-t4.label: t4
Entity-t4.description: t4 refers to a class link in the Wikidata data model that connects the entity wd:Q5, which represents the class of 'human beings', to the schema.org vocabulary under the type 'Person'.

Entity-9367_property_a_of_november_2021.label: 9,367 properties as of November 2021
Entity-9367_property_a_of_november_2021.description: The term '9,367 properties as of November 2021' refers to the number of properties that were officially recognized and documented in Wikidata at that specific time, indicating a subset of the total properties available in the knowledge graph.

Entity-group_of_thing.label: groups of things
Entity-group_of_thing.description: The term 'groups of things' refers to collections of entities or classes within the Wikidata framework that are related to each other and can be described through various properties and relations in the context of the RDF model.

Entity-pillai.label: Pillai
Entity-pillai.description: Pillai refers to an author who, along with co-authors, conducted a comparative analysis of Wikidata and other knowledge graphs (KGs) focusing on data quality criteria such as completeness, timeliness, and accessibility.

Entity-multi-language_aspect.label: multi-language aspects
Entity-multi-language_aspect.description: The term 'multi-language aspects' refers to the various features of Wikidata properties that involve multiple languages, including the labels, descriptions, and aliases used to represent entities in different linguistic contexts.

Entity-the_subgraph.label: the subgraph
Entity-the_subgraph.description: The subgraph refers to the collection of related entities and their attributes that are generated for each unique entity in Wikidata, which includes qualified statements and skolemized IRIs that provide additional context and details about that entity.

Entity-meta-subclass.label: meta-subclass
Entity-meta-subclass.description: The 'meta-subclass' refers to a specific type of relation in Wikidata, denoted as 'is meta-subclass of (P2445)', which indicates a hierarchical relationship between classes, although it is infrequently utilized within the Wikidata framework.

Entity-property_uris.label: property URIs
Entity-property_uris.description: Property URIs refer to the unique identifiers used in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph to represent properties, which are essential for establishing links between entities and external datasets in the context of Linked Data.

Entity-machine_interpretation.label: machine interpretation
Entity-machine_interpretation.description: Machine interpretation refers to the process of automatically understanding and analyzing the alignment properties of Wikidata with various semantic web standards such as RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org.

Entity-instance.label: instances
Entity-instance.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'instances' refer to specific entities that are categorized under a class, exemplified by individuals like Barack Obama, which are linked to their respective classes through the 'instance of' (P31) relation.

Entity-hundred_of_link_to_wikipedia.label: hundreds of links to Wikipedia
Entity-hundred_of_link_to_wikipedia.description: The term 'hundreds of links to Wikipedia' refers to the numerous connections established between entities in Wikidata that have corresponding entries in Wikipedia, facilitating access to additional information about those entities.

Entity-wikimedia.label: WikiMedia
Entity-wikimedia.description: WikiMedia refers to a collaborative organization that operates various free knowledge projects, including Wikipedia and Wikidata, aimed at providing accessible information to the public.

Entity-the_statement_level.label: the statement level
Entity-the_statement_level.description: The statement level refers to the schema of properties and classes used to describe the relationships and attributes of entities within Wikidata, as defined by its internal ontology.

Entity-name_.label: 'name'
Entity-name_.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'name' refers to a property that is used to represent the relationship of an entity's name within the domain-ontology namespace, distinguishing it from other properties that may utilize the RDFS namespace.

Entity-statement.label: statements
Entity-statement.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'statements' refer to the assertions made by the community about entities, which include properties and values that describe those entities within the knowledge graph.

Entity-restriction.label: restrictions
Entity-restriction.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'restrictions' refer to the property constraints defined using the relation property constraint (P2302), which specify limitations on the domain and range of properties within the knowledge graph.

Entity-section_6.label: Section 6
Entity-section_6.description: Section 6 refers to the concluding section of the paper, where the authors summarize their findings and insights regarding the analysis of links in Wikidata and its interconnectedness with other knowledge graphs.

Entity-linked_open_data__lod_.label: Linked Open Data (LOD)
Entity-linked_open_data__lod_.description: Linked Open Data (LOD) refers to a method of publishing structured data on the web in a way that allows it to be interlinked and become more useful through semantic queries.

Entity-lod_ecosystem.label: LOD ecosystem
Entity-lod_ecosystem.description: The LOD ecosystem refers to the interconnected framework of technologies, standards, and practices that facilitate the publishing, sharing, and linking of open data on the web, primarily through the use of linked open data principles.

Entity-a_central_hub_for_linked_data.label: A central hub for Linked Data
aliases: A central hub for Linked Data
Entity-a_central_hub_for_linked_data.description: A central hub for Linked Data refers to a knowledge graph that serves as a reliable linking point for entities, providing persistent identities while connecting to authoritative external sources rather than being the primary source of the data itself.

mentions.local_name: A central hub for Linked Data

Entity-study_on_such_quality_issue.label: studies on such quality issues
Entity-study_on_such_quality_issue.description: The mention 'studies on such quality issues' refers to research efforts that investigate the semantic errors, inconsistencies, and overall quality of the knowledge represented in Wikidata, particularly focusing on its schema level and relationships with other ontologies.

Entity-historical_snapshot_of_the_publis.label: historical snapshots of the published Wikidata HDT files
aliases: historical snapshots of the published Wikidata HDT files
Entity-historical_snapshot_of_the_publis.description: The term 'historical snapshots of the published Wikidata HDT files' refers to archived versions of the Wikidata data represented in the HDT (Header, Dictionary, Triples) format, which allows for the analysis of changes and evolution in the links and structure of Wikidata over time.

mentions.local_name: historical snapshots of the published Wikidata HDT files

Entity-p279.label: P279
Entity-p279.description: 'P279' refers to the 'subclass of' property in Wikidata, which is used to define hierarchical relationships between classes within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-3268021.description: 3,268,021 refers to the number of instance links in Wikidata that use the exact match relation to individuals defined in namespaces other than the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-a_concerted_effort.label: a concerted effort
Entity-a_concerted_effort.description: A concerted effort refers to a collective and coordinated initiative by the community to collaboratively update and enhance existing properties in Wikidata with new relations to improve its interconnectedness with external ontologies.

Entity-it_non-inclusion.label: its non-inclusion
Entity-it_non-inclusion.description: The term 'its non-inclusion' refers to the absence of a mechanism to state disjointness between properties in Wikidata, which was proposed by the community but ultimately not implemented due to the complexities of maintaining such constraints in a collaboratively edited knowledge graph.

Entity-the_other_datasets_in_the_linked_.label: the other datasets in the Linked Open Vocabularies corpus
aliases: the other datasets in the Linked Open Vocabularies corpus
Entity-the_other_datasets_in_the_linked_.description: The other datasets in the Linked Open Vocabularies corpus refer to various datasets that are part of the Linked Open Vocabularies (LOV) initiative, which provides a collection of vocabularies and datasets that are linked and used in the Linked Data ecosystem, characterized by a relatively constant number of class links ranging from 100 to 10,000 per dataset.

mentions.local_name: the other datasets in the Linked Open Vocabularies corpus

Entity-rdf_kg.label: RDF KGs
Entity-rdf_kg.description: RDF KGs refer to knowledge graphs that utilize the Resource Description Framework (RDF) for representing information in a structured format, enabling the integration and sharing of data across different domains.

Entity-different_modelling_choice.label: different modelling choices
Entity-different_modelling_choice.description: Different modelling choices refer to the varying approaches and interpretations adopted by users in defining and organizing classes and instances within the Wikidata framework, which can lead to inconsistencies in the subclass hierarchy.

Entity-different_user.label: different users
Entity-different_user.description: Different users refer to the diverse individuals or stakeholders who contribute to the collaborative development and modeling choices within the Wikidata framework, influencing the structure and classification of entities.

Entity-the_number_of_unique_subject.label: The number of unique subjects
Entity-the_number_of_unique_subject.description: The number of unique subjects refers to the total count of distinct entities represented in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which amounts to 1,625,057,179, indicating the extensive range of subjects covered within this open knowledge graph.

Entity-knowledge_graph__kg_.label: knowledge graph (KG)
Entity-knowledge_graph__kg_.description: A knowledge graph (KG) is a structured representation of knowledge that captures relationships between entities and their attributes, enabling the integration and retrieval of information in a semantic manner.

Entity-2016_version.label: 2016 version
Entity-2016_version.description: The 2016 version refers to a specific release of DBpedia, a community-driven knowledge graph that extracts structured content from the information created in Wikipedia, which includes a total of 8,258 class links across its 3,197 classes.

Entity-target_format_of_the_linked_resou.label: target format of the linked resource
aliases: target format of the linked resource
Entity-target_format_of_the_linked_resou.description: The 'target format of the linked resource' refers to the specific data format (such as RDF or non-RDF) of the resources that are linked from Wikidata to external datasets, which is used to classify the nature of these links in the context of linked data.

mentions.local_name: target format of the linked resource

Entity-web_ontology.label: Web ontology
Entity-web_ontology.description: Web ontology refers to a formal representation of knowledge on the World Wide Web, typically using ontological structures to define the relationships and categories of information for better data interoperability and understanding.

Entity-external_subsuperproperty_relatio.label: external sub/superproperty relation
Entity-external_subsuperproperty_relatio.description: The 'external sub/superproperty relation' refers to a type of property link in the Wikidata data model that involves external properties not explicitly declared as such, which are utilized in subproperty relationships or to define various property characteristics within the context of linked data.

Entity-uri_reuse.label: URI reuse
Entity-uri_reuse.description: URI reuse refers to the practice in ontology engineering of linking an ontology to other ontologies by reusing existing Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) to enhance interoperability and connectivity within the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-unique_object.label: unique objects
Entity-unique_object.description: The term 'unique objects' refers to the distinct entities represented in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, totaling 2,538,585,808, which are used as values in the triples that make up the graph.

Entity-discussion_among_the_editor.label: discussions among the editors
Entity-discussion_among_the_editor.description: The term 'discussions among the editors' refers to the collaborative dialogues and deliberations that take place among the community of editors contributing to Wikidata, aimed at resolving semantic errors, inconsistencies, and improving the overall quality of the knowledge graph.

Entity-a_metaclass.label: A metaclass
Entity-a_metaclass.description: A metaclass is a type of class in Wikidata that serves as the superclass of fixed-order classes, allowing for the organization and categorization of classes of individuals within the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-each_unique_object_uri.label: each unique object URI
Entity-each_unique_object_uri.description: Each unique object URI refers to a distinct identifier for an object in a dataset that is not part of the Wikidata namespace, used to analyze links from Wikidata to external datasets.

Entity-march_2021.label: March 2021
Entity-march_2021.description: March 2021 refers to the specific time when the HDT file for Wikidata was generated, indicating the state of the knowledge graph with 73 million claimed unique entities.

Entity-classesproperties.label: classes/properties
Entity-classesproperties.description: The term 'classes/properties' refers to the defined categories and attributes within the Wikidata namespace that are used to classify and describe entities in the knowledge graph.

Entity-property_that_describe_entitiesre.label: properties that describe entities/relations
Entity-property_that_describe_entitiesre.description: The term 'properties that describe entities/relations' refers to the properties in Wikidata that are used to define relationships and attributes of entities within the same namespace, encompassing both terminological properties and those that establish connections between different entities.

Entity-the_subject.label: the subject
Entity-the_subject.description: In the context of the paper, 'the subject' refers to the entity that appears in the subject position of a triple within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which is a structured representation of data linking various entities and properties.

Entity-owl__sameas_relation.label: owl:sameAs relation
Entity-owl__sameas_relation.description: The owl:sameAs relation is a semantic web concept used to indicate that two different URIs refer to the same entity, but it is not utilized in Wikidata's instance links due to the platform's preference for the exact match relation.

Entity-resource_other_than_rdf.label: resources other than RDF
Entity-resource_other_than_rdf.description: The term 'resources other than RDF' refers to web resources linked from Wikidata that do not have an RDF representation, distinguishing them from RDF entities in the context of linked data.

Entity-open_knowledge_graph.label: open knowledge graphs
Entity-open_knowledge_graph.description: Open knowledge graphs are structured representations of knowledge that are publicly accessible and allow for the integration and sharing of data across various domains.

Entity-authoritative_namespace.label: authoritative namespace
Entity-authoritative_namespace.description: The 'authoritative namespace' in Wikidata refers to the internal framework within which the majority of its terminological entities and properties are defined, ensuring that these definitions are stable and independent from external ontologies.

Entity-every_dataset_publisher.label: Every dataset publisher
Entity-every_dataset_publisher.description: Every dataset publisher refers to any individual or organization that produces and distributes datasets, and is encouraged to create outgoing links in the Wikidata knowledge graph to enhance the visibility and discoverability of their datasets.

Entity-t02__wd__q84263196_rdf__type_sche.label: t02 = wd:Q84263196 rdf:type schema:Dataset
Entity-t02__wd__q84263196_rdf__type_sche.description: The term 't02 = wd:Q84263196 rdf:type schema:Dataset' refers to an instance typing link in Wikidata that classifies the entity Q84263196 as a dataset according to the schema.org vocabulary.

Entity-tool.label: tools
Entity-tool.description: The term 'tools' refers to software and utility applications that are designed to assess and improve various quality aspects of Wikidata and its related WikiMedia projects.

Entity-alias.label: aliases
Entity-alias.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'aliases' refers to alternative names or terms used to identify entities, which are part of the multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties.

Entity-a_framework_to_evaluate_the_ontol.label: a framework to evaluate the ontology as it evolves
aliases: a framework to evaluate the ontology as it evolves
Entity-a_framework_to_evaluate_the_ontol.description: The term 'a framework to evaluate the ontology as it evolves' refers to a proposed systematic approach by Piscopo and Simperl that assesses the quality and development of the Wikidata ontology in relation to the roles of its users.

mentions.local_name: a framework to evaluate the ontology as it evolves

Entity-ontology.label: ontologies
Entity-ontology.description: Ontologies are formal representations of a set of concepts within a domain and the relationships between those concepts, used to enable knowledge sharing and reuse across systems.

Entity-hdt_dump.label: HDT dump
Entity-hdt_dump.description: The HDT dump refers to a compressed binary representation of the entire Wikidata knowledge graph, specifically the dataset as of March 3, 2021, which facilitates efficient storage and retrieval of RDF data.

Entity-process.label: process
Entity-process.description: The term 'process' in this context refers to a systematic method or procedure used to analyze and retrieve Property Links in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-the_developer_of_domain_ontology.label: the developers of domain ontologies
Entity-the_developer_of_domain_ontology.description: The developers of domain ontologies are individuals or groups responsible for creating and maintaining structured frameworks that define the concepts and relationships within specific areas of knowledge, and they are encouraged to establish connections between their ontologies and the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-target_uri_in_an_instance_link.label: target URI in an instance link
aliases: target URI in an instance link
Entity-target_uri_in_an_instance_link.description: The 'target URI in an instance link' refers to a specific Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) that points to an external resource, typically in RDF format, which is linked to an entity defined within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

mentions.local_name: target URI in an instance link

Entity-class_membership.label: class memberships
Entity-class_membership.description: Class memberships refer to the relationships that define the categorization of entities within the Wikidata knowledge graph, specifically indicating which classes an entity belongs to in terms of taxonomic relations.

Entity-authoritative_namespaces.label: authoritative namespaces
aliases: the set of its authoritative namespaces
Entity-authoritative_namespaces.description: Authoritative namespaces refer to the specific URIs defined by Wikidata that denote its own entities and properties, including the namespaces such as http://www.wikidata.org/entity/, http://www.wikidata.org/prop/direct/, and https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Special:EntityData/.

mentions.local_name: the set of its authoritative namespaces

Entity-a_class.label: a class
Entity-a_class.description: In the context of Wikidata and RDF, 'a class' refers to a category or type of entity that can be defined and linked to properties, serving as a foundational element in the structure of the knowledge graph.

Entity-the_predicate.label: the predicate
Entity-the_predicate.description: In the context of the paper, 'the predicate' refers to a component of a triple in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that specifies the relationship between the subject and the object, particularly in the analysis of links to external datasets.

Entity-ds3.label: ds3
Entity-ds3.description: ds3 refers to the schema.org vocabulary, which is used in the context of defining types and properties for structured data on the web.

Entity-iri.label: IRI
Entity-iri.description: IRI refers to an Internationalized Resource Identifier, which is a type of identifier used in the context of RDF and Linked Data to uniquely identify resources, such as entities or properties, within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-external_uris_of_class.label: external URIs of classes
Entity-external_uris_of_class.description: External URIs of classes refer to class identifiers that are sourced from namespaces outside of the Wikidata knowledge graph, which are not recognized by the Wikidata interface's autocomplete feature when linking classes.

Entity-the_declared_class_and_property.label: the declared classes and properties
Entity-the_declared_class_and_property.description: The declared classes and properties refer to the unique classes and properties that are explicitly defined within the ontological framework of various datasets, including those in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-too_strong_formal_ontological_com.label: too strong formal ontological commitment
Entity-too_strong_formal_ontological_com.description: The term 'too strong formal ontological commitment' refers to the intentional avoidance by the Wikidata community of rigidly defining a formal ontology to maintain flexibility and adaptability in the evolving meta-model of Wikidata.

Entity-class_definition.label: class definitions
Entity-class_definition.description: Class definitions in the context of Wikidata refer to the unique classes that are defined within its knowledge graph, which do not utilize rdf:type relations and are therefore considered undeclared according to RDFS/OWL semantics.

Entity-class_item.label: class items
Entity-class_item.description: In Wikidata, 'class items' refer to entities that are categorized as classes within the knowledge graph, specifically represented by the top-level class 'class' (Q16889133), which is a subclass of the broader category 'entity' (Q35120).

Entity-qualified_statement.label: qualified statements
Entity-qualified_statement.description: Qualified statements in Wikidata refer to statements that include additional contextual or provenance information, enhancing the basic item-property-value triples by allowing for the inclusion of metadata about the statements themselves.

Entity-the_ratio.label: the ratio
Entity-the_ratio.description: The ratio refers to the quantitative relationship between the number of class links and the total number of classes in Wikidata, indicating the extent of interlinking between classes within the knowledge graph.

Entity-authoritative_namespace_uris.label: authoritative namespace URIs
Entity-authoritative_namespace_uris.description: Authoritative namespace URIs refer to the specific Uniform Resource Identifiers (URIs) that are officially recognized and defined by various Knowledge Graphs, excluding Wikidata, and are used to identify and link datasets within the Linked Data ecosystem.

Entity-predicate.label: predicate
Entity-predicate.description: In the context of the Wikidata data model, 'predicate' refers to a property that defines a relationship between subjects and objects in RDF triples, specifically used to check conditions for identifying unique object URIs in the analysis of links to external datasets.

Entity-the_community_(1).label: the community
Entity-the_community_(1).description: The community refers to the group of users and contributors involved in the development and maintenance of Wikidata, who proposed the inclusion of disjointness between properties.

Entity-authoritative_source_of_entity.label: authoritative source of entities
Entity-authoritative_source_of_entity.description: The term 'authoritative source of entities' refers to a reliable and recognized dataset or ontology that serves as a definitive reference for specific entities, which Wikidata should link to rather than being considered the primary source itself.

Entity-label__description__and_alias.label: labels, descriptions, and aliases
Entity-label__description__and_alias.description: Labels, descriptions, and aliases in Wikidata refer to the multilingual textual representations associated with entities, providing users with different ways to identify and understand those entities across various languages.

Entity-a_rich_set_of_statement.label: a rich set of statements
Entity-a_rich_set_of_statement.description: A rich set of statements refers to the diverse and extensive assertions made by the community in Wikidata about various entities, which are added without strict adherence to logical consistency, allowing for rapid expansion of the knowledge graph.

Entity-re-definitions_of_those_link.label: re-definitions of those links
Entity-re-definitions_of_those_link.description: The term 're-definitions of those links' refers to the process of reformulating the operationalized SPARQL queries that retrieve various types of links in the Wikidata data model, aligning them with the RDFS/OWL semantics without altering the fundamental definitions of the links themselves.

Entity-the_subject_uri.label: the subject URI
Entity-the_subject_uri.description: The subject URI refers to a unique identifier used in the context of the Wikidata Knowledge Graph to denote the subject of a triple, specifically indicating the entity that is being described or linked to in relation to other datasets or ontologies.

Entity-problematic_classification_and_ta.label: problematic classification and taxonomic statements
