Entity-problematic_classification_and_ta.description: Problematic classification and taxonomic statements refer to inaccuracies or inconsistencies in the categorization and hierarchical organization of entities within Wikidata, which can hinder the effective use and interoperability of the knowledge graph.

Entity-set_of_declared_instance.label: set of declared instances
Entity-set_of_declared_instance.description: The 'set of declared instances' refers to a collection of unique object URIs in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that have been explicitly defined and recognized as instances within the dataset.

Entity-developer.label: developers
Entity-developer.description: The term 'developers' refers to the professionals who create and maintain domain ontologies that can be linked to the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-ontology_namespaces.label: ontology namespaces
Entity-ontology_namespaces.description: Ontology namespaces are structured identifiers used in semantic web technologies to define and differentiate various ontologies, ensuring that terms and concepts are uniquely recognized across different datasets.

Entity-target_uri_(1).label: target URI
Entity-target_uri_(1).description: The term 'target URI' refers to a Uniform Resource Identifier that is linked to an external resource, which may or may not be an RDF resource, in the context of instance links within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-the_linked_data_web.label: the Linked Data Web
Entity-the_linked_data_web.description: The Linked Data Web refers to a framework for interlinking structured data across the internet using standardized formats and protocols, enabling data from different sources to be connected and queried in a unified manner.

Entity-schema__dataset.label: schema:Dataset
Entity-schema__dataset.description: schema:Dataset refers to a class in the Schema.org ontology that represents a structured collection of data, typically used for organizing and sharing information in a machine-readable format.

Entity-work.label: work
Entity-work.description: The mention 'work' refers to a previous research effort that established definitions for two categories of links, specifically ontology links and instance links, in the context of data integration and knowledge graphs.

Entity-range.label: range
Entity-range.description: In the context of ontology and property definitions, 'range' refers to the set of values that a property can take, which is used to define the constraints and relationships of properties within the Wikidata data model.

Entity-object_position.label: object position
Entity-object_position.description: The term 'object position' refers to the role of a URI in the object slot of a triple within the Wikidata knowledge graph, indicating where the data is located in relation to the subject and predicate.

Entity-wikidata_hdt_file.label: Wikidata HDT file
Entity-wikidata_hdt_file.description: The Wikidata HDT file is a compressed binary representation of the Wikidata knowledge base, formatted using the Header, Dictionary, and Triples (HDT) format for efficient storage and retrieval of RDF data.

Entity-p460_and_p1696.label: P460 and P1696
Entity-p460_and_p1696.description: P460 and P1696 refer to specific properties in Wikidata that are not utilized in instance links to entities defined in namespaces other than the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-individual_of_classesproperties.label: individuals of classes/properties
Entity-individual_of_classesproperties.description: The term 'individuals of classes/properties' refers to specific entities within the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that are categorized as instances of defined classes or properties, which are checked for their declaration and definition within the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-an_approach_based_on_cross-compar.label: an approach based on cross-comparing date values
aliases: an approach based on cross-comparing date values
Entity-an_approach_based_on_cross-compar.description: An approach based on cross-comparing date values refers to a methodology used to identify and uncover inconsistencies in temporal data within Wikidata by analyzing and comparing date values across different entries.

Entity-freire_and_isaac.label: Freire and Isaac
Entity-freire_and_isaac.description: Freire and Isaac are researchers who conducted an assessment of Wikidata focusing on its alignment properties with RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org for high-quality machine interpretation.

Entity-nine_datatype_and_object_property.label: nine datatype and object property definitions
aliases: nine datatype and object property definitions
Entity-nine_datatype_and_object_property.description: The term 'nine datatype and object property definitions' refers to the multiple definitions associated with each property in Wikidata, where each property, identified by a 'P' prefix, is linked to up to nine distinct URIs that define its datatype and object properties according to the wikiba.se ontology.

Entity-editor.label: editors
Entity-editor.description: The term 'editors' refers to the community of human contributors who actively participate in the development and maintenance of the Wikidata knowledge graph by adding, modifying, and curating data.

Entity-quality_analysis.label: quality analysis
Entity-quality_analysis.description: Quality analysis refers to the systematic evaluation of the correctness of data within Wikidata, as presented by Shenoy et al.

Entity-it_class.label: its class
Entity-it_class.description: The term 'its class' refers to the specific class in Wikidata to which an instance belongs, as defined by the instance of (P31) relation that connects individual entities to their respective classes.

Entity-link_analysis.label: link analysis
Entity-link_analysis.description: Link analysis is a research methodology used to evaluate relationships and connections between entities in a dataset, often visualized as a network.

Entity-many_work.label: many works
Entity-many_work.description: The term 'many works' refers to various research studies and analyses that investigate different quality aspects of Wikidata.

Entity-1-star_linked_data.label: 1-star linked data
Entity-1-star_linked_data.description: 1-star linked data refers to links in Wikidata that point to non-RDF resources, distinguishing them from higher-ordered linked data that connects to RDF resources.

Entity-hernndez_et_al_..label: Hernández et al.
Entity-hernndez_et_al_..description: Hernández et al. refers to a group of researchers who have conducted a detailed discussion on the relationship between Wikidata's qualified statements and reification, as well as other potential meta-statement encodings in RDF.

Entity-property_equivalent_property__p16.label: property equivalent property (P1628)
Entity-property_equivalent_property__p16.description: The property equivalent property (P1628) in Wikidata is used to indicate that two properties are equivalent, allowing for the establishment of relationships between different properties within the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Entity-domain-ontology_namespace.label: domain-ontology namespace
Entity-domain-ontology_namespace.description: The term 'domain-ontology namespace' refers to a specific namespace used in knowledge graphs, such as FOAF, to define properties that describe domain entities and relations, distinguishing them from the RDFS/OWL namespaces typically used for terminological properties.

Entity-equivalent_property.label: equivalent property
Entity-equivalent_property.description: The 'equivalent property' in Wikidata refers to a specific property (P1628) used to denote that two properties are equivalent in meaning or function within the knowledge graph.

Entity-subject.label: subject
Entity-subject.description: In the context of the paper, 'subject' refers to the position of a class URI within a triple in the Wikidata knowledge graph, specifically indicating whether it appears as the subject or object in the RDF data structure.

Entity-sample.label: sample
Entity-sample.description: The term 'sample' refers to a randomly collected subset of 1,924,940 target URIs from all instance links in Wikidata, used to test the hypothesis regarding the retrieval of RDF documents.

Entity-cross-comparing_date_value.label: cross-comparing date values
Entity-cross-comparing_date_value.description: The term 'cross-comparing date values' refers to a data analysis technique used to identify and discover inconsistencies in temporal data within Wikidata by comparing date values across different entries.

Entity-entity__q35120_.label: entity (Q35120)
Entity-entity__q35120_.description: entity (Q35120) refers to a foundational class in Wikidata that encompasses all items and classes, serving as a universal identifier within the Wikidata framework.

Entity-unique_subject.label: unique subjects
Entity-unique_subject.description: In the context of Wikidata, 'unique subjects' refers to the distinct entities represented in the knowledge graph, totaling 1,625,057,179, which are used as subjects in the RDF triples that comprise the dataset.

Entity-10.22_.description: 10.22% refers to the proportion of all triples in the Wikidata graph that link to individuals defined in namespaces other than the Wikidata namespace.

Entity-low_property_link_ratio.label: low property link ratio
Entity-low_property_link_ratio.description: The term 'low property link ratio' refers to the significantly low average number of external links per property in Wikidata, which is only 0.01, indicating a lack of interconnectedness with other knowledge graphs compared to the average ratios found in the Linked Open Data corpus.

Entity-schema.org.label: schema.org
Entity-schema.org.description: schema.org is a collaborative, community-driven initiative that provides a structured vocabulary for describing data on the web, enabling better interoperability and understanding of web content by search engines and other applications.

Entity-1.62_billion.label: 1.62 billion
Entity-1.62_billion.description: 1.62 billion refers to the number of unique subjects in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, which is significantly larger than the number of unique individuals defined within it.

Entity-exact_match__p2888__relation.label: exact match (P2888) relation
Entity-exact_match__p2888__relation.description: The exact match (P2888) relation is a specific type of link in Wikidata that is used to denote a precise equivalence between entities in different namespaces, as opposed to the more general owl:sameAs relation, which is not permitted in Wikibase.

Entity-n_sds3.label: N Sds3
Entity-n_sds3.description: N Sds3 refers to the namespace identifier for the schema.org vocabulary, which is used in the context of linking data in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-service.label: services
Entity-service.description: The term 'services' refers to tools and resources designed to enhance the quality and completeness of data within the WikiMedia projects, particularly in relation to the analysis of Wikidata.

Entity-item_(1).label: items
Entity-item_(1).description: In Wikidata, 'items' refer to entities that can be classified as either classes or instances, where classes are defined as items in the object position of the 'instance of' (P31) relation or in the subject or object position of a 'subclass of' (P279) statement.

Entity-rdfsowl_namespaces.label: RDFS/OWL namespaces
Entity-rdfsowl_namespaces.description: RDFS/OWL namespaces refer to the standardized namespaces defined by the Resource Description Framework Schema (RDFS) and the Web Ontology Language (OWL) that are typically used in RDF knowledge graphs to define terminological properties and relationships between classes and properties.

Entity-any_triple.label: any triple
Entity-any_triple.description: In the context of the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, 'any triple' refers to a statement composed of a subject, predicate, and object that represents a relationship or property between entities within the graph.

Entity-wd__q84263196.label: wd:Q84263196
Entity-wd__q84263196.description: wd:Q84263196 refers to the entity representing COVID-19 in Wikidata, classified as an instance of the schema:Dataset type.

Entity-frber_et_al_..label: Färber et al.
Entity-frber_et_al_..description: Färber et al. refers to a group of researchers who conducted a comprehensive survey of open knowledge graphs, with a focus on Wikidata.

Entity-piscopo_and_simperl.label: Piscopo and Simperl
Entity-piscopo_and_simperl.description: Piscopo and Simperl are authors who conducted a study on the relationship between different user roles in Wikidata and the quality of its ontology, proposing a framework for evaluating the ontology's evolution.

Entity-wikiba.seontology__statement.label: wikiba.se/ontology#Statement
Entity-wikiba.seontology__statement.description: The entity 'wikiba.se/ontology#Statement' refers to a class in the Wikibase ontology that defines what constitutes a statement for an entity within the Wikidata framework.

Entity-each_property.label: each property
Entity-each_property.description: Each property in Wikidata refers to a defined attribute or relationship, identified by a unique identifier starting with 'P', which encompasses multiple datatype and object property definitions as specified by the wikiba.se ontology.

Entity-1.69_billion_triple.label: 1.69 billion triples
Entity-1.69_billion_triple.description: The mention '1.69 billion triples' refers to the total number of triples in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, indicating its extensive size and complexity compared to other knowledge graphs.

Entity-1_to_41810.label: 1 to 41810
Entity-1_to_41810.description: The term '1 to 41810' refers to the observed ratio of unique subjects to unique predicates in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph, indicating a significantly higher number of predicates relative to subjects compared to other linked data sources.

Entity-item-property-value_triple.label: item-property-value triples
Entity-item-property-value_triple.description: Item-property-value triples are a data structure used in Wikidata to represent statements where an item is associated with a property and a corresponding value, which can be either another item or a literal value.

Entity-historical_snapshot.label: historical snapshots
Entity-historical_snapshot.description: Historical snapshots refer to the archived versions of Wikidata HDT files that allow for the analysis of the evolution of links within the Wikidata knowledge graph over time.

Entity-74309.description: 74,309 refers to the total number of unique declared properties in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph.

Entity-unique_undeclared_property.label: unique undeclared properties
Entity-unique_undeclared_property.description: The term 'unique undeclared properties' refers to the 29,167 properties in the Wikidata Knowledge Graph that have not been formally declared or defined within the Wikidata ontology.

Entity-the_user_interface_s_autocomplete.label: the user interface's autocomplete feature
Entity-the_user_interface_s_autocomplete.description: The user interface's autocomplete feature is a functionality that assists users in quickly finding and selecting classes from the Wikidata namespace while creating links, but it does not support external class URIs.

Entity-ontological_meta-model.label: ontological meta-model
Entity-ontological_meta-model.description: An ontological meta-model is a structured framework that defines the concepts, relationships, and rules governing the representation of knowledge within a specific domain, serving as a higher-level abstraction for organizing and interpreting data and ontologies.

Entity-two_category_of_link.label: two categories of links
Entity-two_category_of_link.description: The term 'two categories of links' refers to the classifications of links in the context of data integration, specifically distinguishing between ontology links, which connect concepts and categories within ontologies, and instance links, which connect specific instances or entities across different datasets.

Entity-ds2.label: ds2

Entity-target_uris.description: Target URIs refer to the specific Uniform Resource Identifiers collected from instance links in Wikidata, which are used to identify and locate resources on the web.

Entity-future_work_(1).description: Future works refers to planned research activities aimed at analyzing the evolution of links in Wikidata over time and conducting a deeper analysis of the entities linked to it.

Entity-link_type_definition.label: link types definitions
Entity-link_type_definition.description: Link types definitions refer to the established categorizations and specifications of different types of connections or relationships between datasets, particularly in the context of ontology links and instance links.

Entity-section_3.description: Section 3 refers to the part of the paper where the authors outline their methodology for analyzing link types in Wikidata.

Entity-completeness_aspect.label: completeness aspect

Entity-other_type_of_web_resource.label: other types of Web resources
Entity-other_type_of_web_resource.description: The mention 'other types of Web resources' refers to various online data sources and formats that are not specifically RDF resources, which may include HTML pages, JSON APIs, or other non-RDF content types that can be linked to from Wikidata.

Entity-the_respective_query_result.label: the respective query results
Entity-the_respective_query_result.description: The respective query results refer to the outcomes obtained from executing SPARQL queries on the Wikidata data model, which quantitatively and qualitatively analyze the discovered links between Wikidata and external datasets.

Entity-expert.label: experts

Entity-tool_and_service.label: tools and services

Entity-schema.org_vocabulary.label: schema.org vocabulary
Entity-schema.org_vocabulary.description: The schema.org vocabulary is a structured collection of terms and definitions used to describe and categorize data on the web, facilitating interoperability and enhancing search engine optimization.

Entity-a_bottom-up_created_knowledge_gra.description: A bottom-up created knowledge graph refers to a type of knowledge graph where properties and entities are added by users in a decentralized manner, allowing for arbitrary additions and modifications without a predefined schema.

Entity-wikimedia_project.label: WikiMedia projects
Entity-wikimedia_project.description: WikiMedia projects refer to a collection of collaborative online platforms and initiatives operated by the WikiMedia Foundation, aimed at creating and sharing free knowledge and content across various formats.

Entity-opaque_identifier.label: opaque identifiers

Entity-each_uri.description: Each URI refers to a Uniform Resource Identifier that is checked by a crawler to determine if it points to a document in RDF format, allowing for the classification of links in Wikidata into Web resources and RDF entities.

Entity-domain_class.label: domain classes

Entity-rdf_meta-model.label: RDF meta-model
Entity-rdf_meta-model.description: The RDF meta-model is a conceptual framework that defines the structure and semantics of data represented in the Resource Description Framework (RDF), facilitating the organization and interoperability of information on the web.

summary:
Wikidata has become one of the most prominent open knowledge graphs (KGs) on the Web. Relying on a community of users with different expertise, this cross-domain KG is directly related to other data sources. This paper investigates how Wikidata is linked to other data sources in the Linked Data ecosystem.

To this end, we adapt previous definitions of ontology links and instance links to the terminological part of the Wikidata vocabulary and perform an analysis of the links in Wikidata to external datasets and ontologies from the Linked Data ecosystem. As a side effect, this reveals insights on the ontological expressiveness of meta-properties used in Wikidata.

The results of this analysis show that while Wikidata defines a large number of individuals, classes and properties within its own namespace, they are not yet extensively linked. We discuss reasons for this and conclude with some suggestions to increase the interconnectedness of Wikidata with other KGs.

Wikidata, a multilingual knowledge graph launched in 2012, contains over 95 million entities and is built collaboratively by editors and bots using the Wikibase software. It integrates external datasets through links, allowing automatic updates, such as citation numbers via bots. This paper aims to study the linkage of Wikidata with other knowledge graphs (KGs) by adapting existing definitions of ontology and instance links to the Wikidata model. The analysis of the HDT dump from March 2021 reveals that Wikidata's ontology is community-developed rather than strictly adhering to RDFS/OWL semantics, leading to semantic inconsistencies that are often resolved through editor discussions. The study proposes hypotheses regarding Wikidata's role as a central hub in the Linked Data ecosystem, focusing on its use of its own namespace for entities, the ratio of internal to external links, and the nature of its instance links. The paper is structured to discuss the ontology in Wikidata, the methodology for analyzing link types, results, related work, and conclusions.

Wikidata utilizes a minimal predefined schema from Wikibase to describe entities, focusing on internal and external links rather than the Wikibase meta-model. Its vocabulary is collaboratively developed, resembling RDFS/OWL properties, but does not strictly adhere to their semantics. This section discusses the meta-modelling classes and relations in Wikidata, mapping them to RDFS/OWL for link analysis. Wikidata differentiates between classes (e.g., person) and instances (e.g., Barack Obama), with a top-level class hierarchy. It includes first-order and second-order classes, with metaclasses defined. While instances can also be subclasses, this can lead to non-intuitive hierarchies. The only consistent assumption is that all items are instances of the entity class, similar to rdfs:Resource in RDF.

Wikidata properties utilize RDF properties to represent both binary relations and atomic value attributes, allowing for item-property-value triples where values can be items or literals. Each statement can be qualified with additional information. Properties have their own Wikidata pages and use identifiers starting with 'P', reusing some RDFS/OWL properties for defining statements about pages. Unlike other RDF knowledge graphs, Wikidata's terminological properties share the same namespace as properties describing entities. Wikidata introduces properties like 'subproperty of' (P1647) to describe hierarchical relations among properties, but these are not linked to external vocabularies. Domain and range properties are defined using qualified property constraints (P2302), with skolemized IRIs for type and value-type constraints. Equivalence between properties is stated with 'equivalent property' (P1628), but disjointness cannot be defined. Wikidata lacks support for property chain axioms and negative property assertions, using property constraints to define restrictions instead.

This text outlines the definition of link types in the Wikidata data model based on RDF-S/OWL correspondences. It discusses the establishment of authoritative namespace URIs from other Knowledge Graphs, utilizing a dataset corpus that includes 431 Linked Datasets totaling 104 GB. The analysis distinguishes between Ontology (TBox) Links and Instance (ABox) Links, with Ontology Links further categorized into class links, instance typing links, property links, and instance role links. SPARQL queries are provided to retrieve these link types, including external classes and properties, and to compute Instance Links from Wikidata to external namespaces. The process involves checking occurrences of classes and properties in the knowledge graph to quantify the links.

This report discusses the link analysis results of Wikidata, conducted on a machine with 8 vCPUs and 380 GB RAM. It highlights that the ratio of unique subjects to predicates in Wikidata is 1 to 41810, compared to 1 to 3900 in the Linked Open Data (LOD) corpus. Wikidata contains 1.69 billion triples, significantly larger than DBpedia's 1.04 billion, indicating that predicate growth in KGs follows an asymptotic function. Wikidata defines 89 million unique individuals using its own ontology, surpassing the 73 million claimed unique entities. Each unique entity typically has about 18 related entities in its subgraph. For instance, Barack Obama has 394 skolemized IRIs detailing his education. Key statistics include 1,693,668,039 triples, 1,625,057,179 unique subjects, 38,867 predicates, and 89,120,227 unique individuals.

This analysis presents statistics on classes and properties in Wikidata, distinguishing between declared and undeclared classes. All 2,522,595 unique classes in Wikidata are undeclared, while properties are declared with owl:DatatypeProperty and owl:ObjectProperty types, totaling 74,309 declared properties as of March 2021. Wikidata has only 3,955 class links, resulting in a low ratio of 0.0015 class links per class, compared to an average of 11.27 in other datasets. This low ratio is attributed to instances being defined as classes and limitations in the user interface. The hypothesis that Wikidata should have more class links is rejected. Similarly, there are only 835 property links, averaging 0.01 per property, leading to the rejection of the hypothesis that Wikidata has more property links than other datasets. The low property link ratio is due to recent additions of properties designed for external linking. Additionally, there are no instance typing links using the instance of relation, confirming the hypothesis that Wikidata types all entities using its own ontology.

Wikidata has 173 million links to entities in other knowledge graphs, representing 10.22% of its triples, but the link ratio of 1.94 is lower than the Linked Open Data ecosystem's 8.6, leading to the rejection of hypothesis H4.1. Many links point to Wikipedia, which are not RDF resources. A sample of 1,924,940 instance links was analyzed, revealing that most point to non-RDF resources, rejecting hypothesis H4.2, although a quarter are RDF resources. Wikidata should classify links based on target formats. In testing hypothesis 5, no instance links used the owl:sameAs relation, and only 3.7% used the exact match relation with external namespaces. Thus, hypothesis 5 is also rejected. Overall, Wikidata has a higher ratio of class and property links compared to the Linked Open Data ecosystem, does not use external ontology classes for typing entities, and most instance links lead to RDF Web resources.

Various studies analyze quality aspects of Wikidata. Erxleben et al. connect Wikidata to the Linked Data Web using RDF exports and identify problematic classifications. Färber et al. survey open KGs, including Wikidata, while Freire and Isaac assess its machine interpretation alignment with RDF/S, OWL, SKOS, and schema.org. Piscopo and Simperl review 28 papers on data quality in Wikidata, focusing on completeness and tools addressing quality. Pillai et al. compare Wikidata with other KGs on completeness, timeliness, and accessibility. Abian et al. discover inconsistent temporal data through cross-comparing date values. Piscopo and Simperl also propose a framework to evaluate the evolving Wikidata ontology based on user roles. Samuel introduces the WDProp tool for multi-language aspects of Wikidata properties, and Shenoy et al. focus on correctness. However, none of these studies analyze Wikidata's interlinking and centrality in the LOD ecosystem, which is the focus of this paper.

We have analysed the number and types of links in Wikidata to evaluate how central Wikidata is to the Linked Open Data ecosystem. While Wikidata is the largest, most comprehensive general knowledge knowledge graph on the Web, using a comprehensive, bottom-up developed ontology that is used to type its many entities, it is not yet serving as a central hub for linked data on the Web.

For its relative lack of instance links, this means that either the Wikidata editors deem such links as obsolete, or that these links are yet to be included, or that they already exist, but rather as incoming links from the external dataset to Wikidata. However, as a bottom-up created knowledge graph, there is the possibility for anyone who owns a dataset to actually create an outgoing link in the Wikidata namespace to the dataset they own. Many bots have been created for exactly this reason, automatically creating outgoing links from Wikidata to other datasets, and they improve the discoverability and visibility of the external dataset. Every dataset publisher, for their own benefit, should therefore consider creating those outgoing links in the Wikidata knowledge graph.

Comparatively, for its size, Wikidata also includes less ontology links than other datasets in the Linked Open Data ecosystem. While this can be partially explained by the fact that many individuals defined in Wikidata are also classes, skewing the ratio between classes and class links, this does not apply to property links, where there is no such distinction. Most properties in Wikidata are not linked to external properties at all, even though specific properties exist in the Wikidata ontology to do so.

While we have suggested in this paper that some changes to the user interface of Wikibase may encourage editors to provide more such links, a fundamental rethink of ontology design may have to occur too. Specifically, common best practice in ontology engineering is to include links from an ontology to other ontologies through import statements or URI reuse. However, in the case of the Wikidata ontology, the developers of domain ontologies should consider creating those links to their ontologies in the Wikidata namespace, rather than in the other direction.

Wikidata also does not yet provide many equivalence or weaker forms of likeness relations from its entities to external entities. There is an onus on the Wikidata editor community to ensure that such links are increasingly provided, given that Wikidata should generally not be the authoritative source of entities, but link to an authoritative representation of an entity through, for example, the exact match relation in Wikidata. However, the lack of such links may also be an indication that entities defined in Wikidata do not yet exist or never will exist in the Linked Open Data ecosystem.

As future works, we first would like to analyse the evolution of links on Wikidata over time using several historical snapshots of the published Wikidata HDT files. Also, a deeper analysis of the entities that are linked, such as what are the top-ranked instance and ontology namespaces referenced from Wikidata, is planned for future work.

Predicate-are_on.label: are on
Predicate-are_on.description: The predicate 'are on' indicates a state of existence or presence, connecting the subject to the object by expressing that the subject is located, situated, or available within the context or domain represented by the object. It implies a relationship where the subject is accessible or relevant in the environment or platform denoted by the object.

Predicate-is_related_to.label: is related to
Predicate-is_related_to.description: The predicate 'is related to' establishes a connection or association between the subject and the object, indicating that there is a relevant link, correlation, or relationship between the two entities. This relationship can encompass various forms of connections, such as semantic, functional, or contextual ties, suggesting that the subject and object share some commonality or relevance in a broader context.

Predicate-is_directly_related_to.label: is directly related to
Predicate-is_directly_related_to.description: The predicate 'is directly related to' establishes a direct connection or association between the subject and the object, indicating that they share a significant relationship or relevance to each other. This relationship can imply that the subject influences, is influenced by, or has a meaningful interaction with the object, highlighting the importance of their connection in a broader context.

Predicate-investigates_how.label: investigates how
Predicate-investigates_how.description: The predicate 'investigates how' establishes a relationship where the subject conducts an inquiry or analysis into the methods, processes, or mechanisms related to the object. It implies a systematic exploration aimed at understanding the underlying principles or functioning of the object in question.

Predicate-is_linked_to.label: is linked to
Predicate-is_linked_to.description: The predicate 'is linked to' establishes a relationship of connection or association between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject has a relevant or significant relationship with the object. This can imply various forms of linkage, such as data relationships, references, or dependencies, suggesting that the subject and object are part of a broader network or system.

Predicate-adapted_to.label: adapted to
Predicate-adapted_to.description: The predicate 'adapted to' indicates a relationship where the subject has been modified, tailored, or designed to fit the requirements, characteristics, or context of the object. This suggests a level of compatibility or suitability between the two entities, where the subject is effectively aligned or adjusted to serve the needs or functions associated with the object.

Predicate-perform_an_analysis_of.label: perform an analysis of
Predicate-perform_an_analysis_of.description: The predicate 'perform an analysis of' indicates an action where the subject engages in a systematic examination or evaluation of the object. This involves investigating, interpreting, or assessing the characteristics, relationships, or implications of the object in order to derive insights, conclusions, or understanding. The subject is typically an entity or agent that conducts the analysis, while the object represents the data, information, or materials being analyzed.

Predicate-analyzed_in.label: analyzed in
Predicate-analyzed_in.description: The predicate 'analyzed in' indicates that the subject is examined, studied, or evaluated within the context or framework of the object. It suggests a relationship where the subject is subjected to scrutiny or investigation, and the findings or insights derived from this analysis are relevant to the object, which serves as the setting or domain of the analysis.

Predicate-adapt_to.label: adapt to
Predicate-adapt_to.description: The predicate 'adapt to' signifies a process of modification or adjustment where the subject undergoes changes to align with or accommodate the characteristics, requirements, or structure of the object. This relationship implies that the subject is flexible and responsive, enabling it to integrate or function effectively within the context defined by the object.

Predicate-reveals_insights_on.label: reveals insights on
Predicate-reveals_insights_on.description: The predicate 'reveals insights on' indicates a relationship where the subject provides or uncovers valuable information, understanding, or knowledge regarding the object. This connection suggests that the subject serves as a source or medium through which deeper comprehension or analysis of the object is achieved, facilitating a clearer or more profound grasp of the topic at hand.

Predicate-used_in.label: used in
Predicate-used_in.description: The predicate 'used in' establishes a relationship where the subject is applied, implemented, or utilized within the context of the object. It indicates that the subject plays a role or serves a function in the environment or system represented by the object.

Predicate-defines.label: defines
Predicate-defines.description: The predicate 'defines' establishes a relationship in which the subject provides a clear and specific explanation or characterization of the object, indicating that the object is a concept, category, or entity that is being described or identified by the subject.

Predicate-has.label: has
Predicate-has.description: The predicate 'has' indicates a possessive relationship between the subject and the object, signifying that the subject contains, owns, or is associated with the object in some capacity. It establishes a connection where the subject is the entity that possesses the attribute or characteristic represented by the object.

Predicate-interconnectedness_with.label: interconnectedness with
Predicate-interconnectedness_with.description: The predicate 'interconnectedness with' denotes a relationship where the subject is linked or associated with the object in a manner that highlights mutual relevance, influence, or interaction. This connection implies that both entities share common elements, data, or functionalities, facilitating a network of relationships that enhances their collective value and usability. In this context, the subject and object are part of a broader ecosystem where their interrelations contribute to a more comprehensive understanding or functionality.

Predicate-conclude_with.label: conclude with
Predicate-conclude_with.description: The predicate 'conclude with' indicates that the subject presents a final statement, summary, or outcome that is directly related to the object. It implies that the subject leads to a logical or thematic closure, where the object serves as the concluding element that encapsulates or explains the preceding content.

Predicate-are_not_yet_extensively_linked.label: are not yet extensively linked
Predicate-are_not_yet_extensively_linked.description: The predicate 'are not yet extensively linked' indicates a lack of significant or comprehensive connections between the subject and the object. It suggests that while some degree of association may exist, the relationship is not fully developed or utilized, implying potential for future integration or collaboration.

Predicate-with.label: with
Predicate-with.description: The predicate 'with' indicates a relationship of association or connection between the subject and the object, suggesting that they exist together or are involved in a shared context or interaction. It implies a collaborative or complementary nature, where the subject and object are linked in a way that enhances understanding of their roles or functions.

Predicate-discusses.label: discusses
Predicate-discusses.description: The predicate 'discusses' indicates a communicative action where the subject engages in a conversation or dialogue about a specific topic or concept represented by the object. It implies an exchange of ideas, opinions, or information, often aiming to explore, analyze, or clarify the subject matter at hand.

Predicate-linked_to.label: linked to
Predicate-linked_to.description: The predicate 'linked to' indicates a relationship of connection or association between the subject and the object, suggesting that the subject has a relevant or significant relationship with the object. In the context of knowledge graphs, this often implies that the subject is related to or interacts with the object in a meaningful way, facilitating the integration or comparison of information across different entities or datasets.

Predicate-has_grown_to.label: has grown to
Predicate-has_grown_to.description: The predicate 'has grown to' indicates a developmental progression or increase in scale, complexity, or significance of the subject, leading to the state or condition represented by the object. It suggests that the subject has undergone a transformation or expansion that results in the current state denoted by the object.

Predicate-containing.label: containing
Predicate-containing.description: The predicate 'containing' establishes a relationship between the subject and the object by indicating that the subject includes or holds within it the elements represented by the object. It signifies that the subject encompasses a specific quantity or type of items, which are detailed in the object, thereby providing information about the composition or contents of the subject.

Predicate-is.label: is
Predicate-is.description: The predicate 'is' serves as a linking verb that establishes an identity or equivalence between the subject and the object. It indicates that the subject can be classified or defined in terms of the object, suggesting that they belong to the same category or share a common characteristic.

Predicate-contains.label: contains
Predicate-contains.description: The predicate 'contains' is used to indicate that the subject includes or holds within it the object, which can be a quantity, item, or concept. It establishes a relationship where the subject is seen as a container or source that possesses the object, highlighting the presence or existence of the object as part of the subject's attributes or components.

Predicate-has_been_conceived_as.label: has been conceived as
Predicate-has_been_conceived_as.description: The predicate 'has been conceived as' indicates a conceptualization or interpretation of the subject in relation to the object. It suggests that the subject is understood or defined in a particular way that aligns with the characteristics or functions represented by the object. This predicate often implies a theoretical or abstract framework within which the subject is placed, highlighting the relationship between the two entities in terms of ideas, roles, or classifications.

Predicate-is_built_by.label: is built by
Predicate-is_built_by.description: The predicate 'is built by' indicates a relationship where the subject is constructed, developed, or created through the efforts, contributions, or actions of the object. It emphasizes the role of the object as the agent or source responsible for the formation or assembly of the subject.

Predicate-allows.label: allows
Predicate-allows.description: The predicate 'allows' indicates that the subject provides permission, opportunity, or capability for the object to perform an action or to exist in a certain state. It establishes a relationship where the subject facilitates or enables the object in some manner.

Predicate-uses.label: uses
Predicate-uses.description: The predicate 'uses' indicates a functional relationship where the subject employs or utilizes the object as a tool, resource, or method to achieve a specific purpose or outcome. It signifies that the subject actively incorporates the object into its operations or processes.

Predicate-creates.label: creates
Predicate-creates.description: The predicate 'creates' indicates an action performed by the subject that results in the formation or establishment of the object. It signifies a generative process where the subject initiates the existence of the object, which can be a tangible or intangible entity, such as a product, concept, or system.

Predicate-allow.label: allow
Predicate-allow.description: The predicate 'allow' indicates that the subject provides the necessary conditions or permissions for the object to exist, function, or be utilized. It signifies a relationship where the subject facilitates or enables the object, thereby creating an opportunity for the object to be accessed, used, or realized.

Predicate-is_for_creating.label: is for creating
Predicate-is_for_creating.description: The predicate 'is for creating' establishes a purpose or function relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject is intended or designed to facilitate the development or generation of the object. In this context, the subject serves as a tool, platform, or system that enables the production or assembly of the object, which represents a specific type of output or outcome.

Predicate-reuse.label: reuse
Predicate-reuse.description: The predicate 'reuse' indicates the action of employing or utilizing something again, typically in a different context or for a different purpose. In the context of the subject and object, it signifies that the subject is taking previously established or existing items, concepts, or resources and applying them anew to the object, thereby enhancing their value or functionality without the need for creating new instances from scratch.

Predicate-integrate.label: integrate
Predicate-integrate.description: The predicate 'integrate' denotes the action of combining or unifying different elements or components into a cohesive whole. In the context of the subject and object, it implies that the subject is actively involved in the process of merging or synthesizing the object with other elements, resulting in a more comprehensive or functional entity.

Predicate-from.label: from
Predicate-from.description: The predicate 'from' indicates the origin or source of the subject, establishing a relationship where the subject is derived, obtained, or sourced from the object. It connects the subject to the object by specifying that the subject's existence, characteristics, or content is linked to or originates from the object.

Predicate-under_the_control_of.label: under the control of
Predicate-under_the_control_of.description: The predicate 'under the control of' indicates a relationship where the subject is governed, managed, or influenced by the object. It implies that the object has authority or oversight over the subject, suggesting a hierarchical or supervisory connection. This relationship often involves the object having the power to make decisions or enforce rules that affect the subject.

Predicate-updates.label: updates
Predicate-updates.description: The predicate 'updates' signifies an action where the subject performs a modification or enhancement to the object, typically involving the incorporation of new information or changes to existing data. In this context, it indicates that the subject is actively engaged in the process of refreshing or revising the state of the object to reflect the most current or accurate information.

Predicate-exists_on.label: exists on
Predicate-exists_on.description: The predicate 'exists on' indicates that the subject is present, available, or located within the context or framework of the object. It establishes a relationship where the subject is associated with, or operates within, the domain defined by the object.

Predicate-has_become.label: has become
Predicate-has_become.description: The predicate 'has become' indicates a transformation or change in state, signifying that the subject has transitioned into or assumed the characteristics or role of the object. It implies a process of evolution or development where the subject is now identified or recognized as the object, reflecting a new identity or function.

Predicate-motivate.label: motivate
Predicate-motivate.description: The predicate 'motivate' indicates a relationship where the subject provides a reason, encouragement, or impetus for the action or consideration represented by the object. It suggests that the subject's qualities, characteristics, or findings inspire or drive the need for further exploration, action, or understanding as expressed in the object.

Predicate-on.label: on
Predicate-on.description: The predicate 'on' is used to indicate the subject's focus or area of discussion, research, or analysis in relation to the object. It establishes a thematic connection where the subject is concerned with, examines, or elaborates upon the concepts, issues, or topics represented by the object.

Predicate-links_with.label: links with
Predicate-links_with.description: The predicate 'links with' indicates a relationship of connection or association between the subject and the object, suggesting that the subject has established a form of linkage, collaboration, or interaction with the object. This can imply sharing information, data, or resources, and often denotes a networked relationship where both entities may influence or enhance each other's functionality or accessibility.

Predicate-involves.label: involves
Predicate-involves.description: The predicate 'involves' indicates a relationship where the subject encompasses or requires the object as a necessary component or aspect. It suggests that the subject cannot be fully understood or executed without considering the object, which provides essential details or elements that contribute to the overall context or function of the subject.

Predicate-has_established.label: has established
Predicate-has_established.description: The predicate 'has established' indicates that the subject has created, confirmed, or recognized a certain relationship, principle, or framework represented by the object. It implies a sense of authority or foundational contribution made by the subject in relation to the object, suggesting that the object is a result of the subject's efforts or findings.

Predicate-between.label: between
Predicate-between.description: The predicate 'between' indicates a relational context in which the subject is positioned in relation to the object, suggesting a connection, interaction, or distinction that exists in the space or framework defined by both entities. It implies that the subject serves as a mediator or a point of reference that delineates or facilitates a relationship involving the object.

Predicate-established.label: established
Predicate-established.description: The predicate 'established' indicates that the subject has created, confirmed, or recognized a certain state of knowledge, relationship, or framework regarding the object. It implies a process of setting up or formalizing connections or definitions that are acknowledged as valid or authoritative within a particular context.

Predicate-defined.label: defined
Predicate-defined.description: The predicate 'defined' establishes a relationship in which the subject provides a clear and specific explanation or characterization of the object. It indicates that the subject articulates the meaning, scope, or nature of the object, thereby clarifying its identity or function within a particular context.

Predicate-defined_(1).label: defined
Predicate-defined_(1).description: The predicate 'defined' establishes a relationship where the subject provides a specific meaning, explanation, or characterization for the object. It indicates that the subject clarifies or specifies the nature or attributes of the object, thereby creating a clear understanding of what the object represents or entails.

Predicate-aim_to_apply.label: aim to apply
Predicate-aim_to_apply.description: The predicate 'aim to apply' indicates an intention or goal of the subject to utilize or implement the object in a practical context. It suggests a proactive approach where the subject seeks to integrate the object into their activities or processes, reflecting a desire to achieve a specific outcome through the application of the object.

Predicate-aim_to_re-use_and_adapt.label: aim to re-use and adapt
Predicate-aim_to_re-use_and_adapt.description: The predicate 'aim to re-use and adapt' expresses the intention of the subject to take existing materials, concepts, or definitions and modify them for new purposes or contexts. It indicates a proactive approach to utilizing prior knowledge or resources in a way that enhances their relevance or applicability, thereby fostering innovation and efficiency.

Predicate-evaluates.label: evaluates
Predicate-evaluates.description: The predicate 'evaluates' signifies an assessment or analysis performed by the subject on the object, indicating that the subject is determining the quality, effectiveness, or value of the object in a systematic manner.

Predicate-of.label: of
Predicate-of.description: The predicate 'of' is used to indicate a relationship of belonging or association between the subject and the object. It signifies that the subject is a representation, subset, or specific instance that is derived from or related to the object, establishing a connection that often implies origin, content, or thematic relevance.

Predicate-does_not_rely_on.label: does not rely on
Predicate-does_not_rely_on.description: The predicate 'does not rely on' indicates a relationship where the subject operates independently of the object, suggesting that the subject does not depend on the object for its functionality, structure, or validity. This implies a lack of necessity or influence from the object in the context of the subject's existence or operation.

Predicate-are_established_for.label: are established for
Predicate-are_established_for.description: The predicate 'are established for' indicates a foundational or supportive relationship between the subject and the object, suggesting that the subject serves a purpose or function that is specifically aligned with the object. Predicate-builds.label: builds

It implies a process of assembling or forming something new from various components or ideas, often involving effort, collaboration, or planning. In this context, the subject is actively engaged in producing or establishing the object, which can be a tangible or intangible entity.

Predicate-tries_to_re-use_and_integrate.label: tries to re-use and integrate
Predicate-tries_to_re-use_and_integrate.description: The predicate 'tries to re-use and integrate' indicates an effort by the subject to adopt and incorporate elements from the object into its own framework or system. This involves utilizing existing resources or structures in a way that enhances the subject's functionality or knowledge base, while also ensuring compatibility and coherence with the object.

This connection often implies that the subject is related to or supports the object in some way, facilitating access to additional information, resources, or contexts that are relevant to the subject.

Predicate-linked_through.label: linked through
Predicate-linked_through.description: The predicate 'linked through' indicates a connection or relationship between the subject and object, suggesting that the subject is associated with the object via a specific mechanism, pathway, or intermediary. This connection often implies a form of interaction, correlation, or dependency that facilitates the integration or communication between the two entities.

Predicate-include.label: include
Predicate-include.description: The predicate 'include' denotes a relationship where the subject encompasses or contains the object as a part of its broader category or set. It indicates that the object is a component or element that is inherently part of the subject, suggesting a hierarchical or associative connection between the two.

Predicate-introduces.label: introduces
Predicate-introduces.description: The predicate 'introduces' signifies the act of presenting or bringing forth a new concept, idea, or entity to an audience or context, establishing a connection between the subject and the object. In this context, the subject is the entity that is making the introduction, while the object is the concept or entity being presented, indicating a relationship where the subject plays a role in making the object known or accessible.

Predicate-extends.label: extends
Predicate-extends.description: The predicate 'extends' indicates a relationship where the subject provides additional scope, coverage, or influence to the object, suggesting that the subject enhances or enlarges the object in some manner.

Predicate-adds.label: adds
Predicate-adds.description: The predicate 'adds' indicates an action where the subject contributes or incorporates something new into a larger context or collection, resulting in an increase or enhancement of the object. It signifies a positive change or augmentation that the subject brings to the object, suggesting a relationship of growth or enrichment.

Predicate-about.label: about
Predicate-about.description: The predicate 'about' serves to establish a relationship of relevance or focus between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject provides information, context, or commentary concerning the object. It implies that the subject is centered on or pertains to the object, thereby linking the two in a way that highlights the subject's connection to the themes, topics, or entities represented by the object.

Predicate-concerns.label: concerns
Predicate-concerns.description: The predicate 'concerns' establishes a relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject is related to, involved with, or has relevance to the object. It suggests that the subject has an interest in, or is affected by, the aspects or issues represented by the object.

Predicate-expect.label: expect
Predicate-expect.description: The predicate 'expect' denotes a relationship where the subject holds a belief or anticipation regarding the object, implying that the subject considers the object to be a likely or necessary outcome based on certain criteria or conditions.

Predicate-is_extended_by.label: is extended by

It signifies that the object plays a role in adding value, information, or functionality to the subject, thereby broadening its scope or capabilities.

Predicate-is_added_by.label: is added by
Predicate-is_added_by.description: The predicate 'is added by' indicates a relationship where the subject is enhanced, supplemented, or expanded through the contributions or actions of the object. It signifies that the object plays an active role in providing additional elements, features, or information to the subject, thereby enriching its overall quality or quantity.

Predicate-comes_with.label: comes with
Predicate-comes_with.description: The predicate 'comes with' indicates that the subject is associated with or includes the object as a part of its nature, characteristics, or consequences. It suggests that the object is an inherent or expected aspect that accompanies the subject, often implying a relationship where the subject cannot be fully understood or appreciated without acknowledging the presence of the object.

Predicate-are_prevalent_in.label: are prevalent in
Predicate-are_prevalent_in.description: The predicate 'are prevalent in' indicates that the subject is commonly found or frequently occurring within the context or domain specified by the object. Predicate-are_resolved_through.label: are resolved through
Predicate-are_resolved_through.description: The predicate 'are resolved through' indicates a process or method by which the subject achieves a solution or conclusion regarding an issue or challenge, with the object representing the means or approach utilized in this resolution. Predicate-relates_to.label: relates to

Predicate-is_contained_within.label: is contained within
Predicate-is_contained_within.description: The predicate 'is contained within' establishes a relationship where the subject represents an entity or concept that exists as a part or subset of the object, which is a larger entity or framework. Predicate-are_to.label: are to

Predicate-maps_to.label: maps to

Predicate-is_presented_by.label: is presented by

Predicate-is_mapped_to.label: is mapped to
Predicate-is_mapped_to.description: The predicate 'is mapped to' indicates a relationship where the subject is associated with or corresponds to the object in a specific context or framework. Predicate-compared_to.label: compared to

Predicate-allows_to_analyze.label: allows to analyze

Predicate-links_from.label: links from

Predicate-is_central_to.label: is central to
Predicate-is_central_to.description: The predicate 'is central to' indicates that the subject plays a crucial or pivotal role in relation to the object, suggesting that the object is significantly influenced by, dependent on, or fundamentally connected to the subject. This relationship implies that the subject is a key component or foundational element within the context of the object.

Predicate-are_tested_in.label: are tested in
Predicate-are_tested_in.description: The predicate 'are tested in' indicates that the subject is subjected to evaluation, examination, or experimentation within the context or framework provided by the object. It implies a process of verification or validation where the subject's validity, reliability, or effectiveness is assessed through the methodologies or criteria defined in the object.

Predicate-tests.label: tests
Predicate-tests.description: The predicate 'tests' indicates an action or process in which the subject evaluates, examines, or assesses the validity, reliability, or performance of the object. Predicate-are_defined_within.label: are defined within
Predicate-are_defined_within.description: The predicate 'are defined within' establishes a relationship where the subject is situated or categorized inside the boundaries or context specified by the object. It indicates that the subject's existence, characteristics, or functionality are contingent upon or derived from the framework or environment represented by the object.

Predicate-represent.label: represent
Predicate-represent.description: The predicate 'represent' establishes a relationship where the subject serves as a symbol, depiction, or manifestation of the object. It indicates that the subject conveys, illustrates, or embodies the characteristics, qualities, or essence of the object, thereby creating a connection between the two entities.

Predicate-exhibits.label: exhibits
Predicate-exhibits.description: The predicate 'exhibits' denotes a relationship in which the subject actively displays, demonstrates, or presents the object, which can be a characteristic, behavior, or phenomenon. This connection implies that the subject has the capacity or quality to reveal the object in a manner that is observable or recognizable.

Predicate-observed_in.label: observed in
Predicate-observed_in.description: The predicate 'observed in' indicates a relationship where the subject has been noted, detected, or recorded within the context or framework of the object. It suggests that the subject's presence, characteristics, or phenomena have been identified or documented in the specified object, which often serves as a source, database, or reference point for the information.

Predicate-tested_in.label: tested in
Predicate-tested_in.description: The predicate 'tested in' indicates that the subject has undergone a process of evaluation or experimentation in relation to the object. It signifies that the subject has been subjected to a specific test or assessment that is associated with the object, which often represents a theory, hypothesis, or experimental condition. This connection implies a relationship where the subject's performance, validity, or applicability is being examined in the context of the object.

Predicate-has_observed.label: has observed
Predicate-has_observed.description: The predicate 'has observed' indicates that the subject has actively perceived or noted the existence, characteristics, or behavior of the object. It implies a process of examination or study, suggesting that the subject has gathered information or insights about the object through direct or indirect observation.

Predicate-are_defined_in.label: are defined in
Predicate-are_defined_in.description: The predicate 'are defined in' establishes a relationship where the subject is characterized or specified by the object, indicating that the subject's meaning, scope, or context is provided or clarified within the framework of the object. This connection implies that the object serves as a reference point or source of authority for understanding the subject.

Predicate-is_part_of.label: is part of
Predicate-is_part_of.description: The predicate 'is part of' establishes a relationship where the subject is identified as a component, element, or subset of the object. This indicates that the subject contributes to or is included within the broader context or structure represented by the object, suggesting a hierarchical or associative connection between the two.

Predicate-has_a_larger_ratio_of_property.label: has a larger ratio of property links to properties defined within

Predicate-does_not_type.label: does not type
Predicate-does_not_type.description: The predicate 'does not type' indicates a relationship where the subject is not classified or categorized as the object. It signifies the absence of a specific type or classification that would typically connect the subject to the object in a definitional or categorical manner.

Predicate-using.label: using
Predicate-using.description: The predicate 'using' indicates a relationship where the subject employs or utilizes the object as a means, method, or resource to achieve a specific purpose or function. It signifies that the subject actively engages with the object in a way that facilitates or enhances its operations or processes.

Predicate-are.label: are
Predicate-are.description: The predicate 'are' serves as a linking verb that establishes a relationship of identity or classification between the subject and the object. It indicates that the subject is defined or characterized by the object, suggesting that the subject belongs to a category or possesses the qualities described by the object.

Predicate-includes_links_from.label: includes links from
Predicate-includes_links_from.description: The predicate 'includes links from' establishes a relationship where the subject contains or references connections originating from the object. It indicates that the subject is enriched or supplemented by the presence of links that are derived from the specified entities or sources represented by the object.

Predicate-to_entities_defined_in.label: to entities defined in
Predicate-to_entities_defined_in.description: The predicate 'to entities defined in' establishes a relationship between a subject and an object by indicating that the subject is associated with or refers to specific entities that are defined or cataloged within the context of the object. Predicate-is_larger_than_for.label: is larger than for

This predicate is used to express that the subject exceeds the object in a specific dimension, which can pertain to data volume, complexity, or any measurable attribute relevant to the subject's domain.

Predicate-is_in.label: is in
Predicate-is_in.description: The predicate 'is in' establishes a relationship of inclusion or membership between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject exists within the context, category, or collection represented by the object. It signifies that the subject is part of a larger whole or is contained within the boundaries defined by the object.

Predicate-is_a.label: is a
Predicate-is_a.description: The predicate 'is a' establishes a classification or categorization relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject belongs to the category or type defined by the object. It signifies that the subject can be understood as an instance or example of the broader concept represented by the object.

Predicate-is_relatively_higher_than.label: is relatively higher than
Predicate-is_relatively_higher_than.description: The predicate 'is relatively higher than' establishes a comparative relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject possesses a greater degree, quantity, or quality in relation to the object within a specific context. This comparison suggests that when evaluating the subject against the object, the subject is found to exceed the object in some measurable aspect.

Predicate-in_an_instance_link.label: in an instance link
Predicate-in_an_instance_link.description: The predicate 'in an instance link' establishes a relationship between a subject and an object by indicating that the subject is associated with or represented in the context of the object, typically within a framework that utilizes instance-based linking. Predicate-is_a_common.label: is a common
Predicate-is_a_common.description: The predicate 'is a common' establishes a relationship of generality or prevalence between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject is frequently encountered or widely recognized in the context of the object. It suggests that the subject is a typical or standard example of the object category.

Predicate-tests_for.label: tests for
Predicate-tests_for.description: The predicate 'tests for' indicates a relationship where the subject is evaluating or examining the presence, validity, or characteristics of the object. It implies that the subject is conducting an investigation or analysis to determine whether the object meets certain criteria or conditions.

Predicate-is_claimed_to_be.label: is claimed to be
Predicate-is_claimed_to_be.description: The predicate 'is claimed to be' indicates a statement or assertion made about the subject, suggesting that the subject is regarded or presented as the object. This implies a belief or opinion held by someone or a group regarding the nature, identity, or status of the subject, without necessarily confirming its truth or validity.

Predicate-provides.label: provides
Predicate-provides.description: The predicate 'provides' indicates a relationship in which the subject offers, supplies, or makes available a particular resource, service, or attribute to the object. It signifies that the subject plays a role in fulfilling a need or requirement represented by the object, establishing a connection where the subject is the source or provider of the specified element.

Predicate-establishes.label: establishes
Predicate-establishes.description: The predicate 'establishes' indicates the action of creating, instituting, or formalizing a connection or relationship between the subject and the object. It implies that the subject plays a role in bringing about the existence or recognition of the object, which can represent concepts, categories, or types of relationships. In this context, 'establishes' suggests a foundational or authoritative role of the subject in defining or clarifying the nature of the object.

Predicate-are_part_of.label: are part of
Predicate-are_part_of.description: The predicate 'are part of' indicates a relationship of inclusion or membership, where the subject is a component or element that contributes to the whole represented by the object. This connection implies that the subject cannot be fully understood without considering its relationship to the object, as the object encompasses or contains the subject within a broader context.

Predicate-analyzes.label: analyzes
Predicate-analyzes.description: The predicate 'analyzes' indicates an action where the subject systematically examines, inspects, or studies the object in order to understand its structure, components, or relationships. This process often involves breaking down the object into its constituent parts to gain insights or draw conclusions based on the findings.

Predicate-presents.label: presents
Predicate-presents.description: The predicate 'presents' indicates an action where the subject introduces, displays, or provides information about the object, typically in a structured or formal manner. It signifies the act of making the object known to an audience, often with the intention of conveying findings, results, or insights derived from a particular analysis or study.

Predicate-tested_on.label: tested on
Predicate-tested_on.description: The predicate 'tested on' indicates a relationship where the subject, typically a theory, hypothesis, or model, is evaluated or examined using the object, which represents the dataset, environment, or context in which the testing occurs. This connection implies that the subject's validity, effectiveness, or performance is assessed based on the characteristics or contents of the object.

Predicate-are_based_on.label: are based on
Predicate-are_based_on.description: The predicate 'are based on' indicates a foundational relationship where the subject derives its principles, conclusions, or framework from the object. It suggests that the subject's validity, reasoning, or development is contingent upon the information, data, or context provided by the object.

Predicate-concludes.label: concludes
Predicate-concludes.description: The predicate 'concludes' indicates that the subject provides a final statement, summary, or resolution regarding the object. It signifies the act of bringing a discussion, analysis, or argument to a close, often highlighting key points or findings related to the object.

Predicate-is_discussed_in.label: is discussed in
Predicate-is_discussed_in.description: The predicate 'is discussed in' establishes a relationship where the subject is the topic or concept that is elaborated upon or analyzed within the context of the object, which typically refers to a specific section, chapter, or part of a document or text. This indicates that the subject is a focal point of discussion or examination in the specified location.

Predicate-relies_on.label: relies on
Predicate-relies_on.description: The predicate 'relies on' indicates a dependency or reliance relationship between the subject and the object, where the subject requires the object for support, functionality, or operation. This connection suggests that the subject's existence, effectiveness, or performance is contingent upon the object.

Predicate-is_used_to_describe.label: is used to describe
Predicate-is_used_to_describe.description: The predicate 'is used to describe' establishes a relationship where the subject provides a characterization, definition, or explanation of the object. It indicates that the subject serves as a means or framework for understanding the qualities, attributes, or functions of the object.

Predicate-constitutes.label: constitutes
Predicate-constitutes.description: The predicate 'constitutes' establishes a relationship where the subject is identified as a fundamental or essential part of the object, indicating that the subject forms a significant component or basis for the object in question.

Predicate-is_a_type_of.label: is a type of
Predicate-is_a_type_of.description: The predicate 'is a type of' establishes a hierarchical relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that the subject belongs to a broader category or classification represented by the object. It signifies that the subject is an instance or specific example of the general concept defined by the object, thereby contributing to the organization and understanding of knowledge within a structured framework.

Predicate-distinguishes_between.label: distinguishes between

It implies a comparative analysis that highlights the differences or unique features that set apart the object from other similar entities or classifications.

Predicate-is_irrelevant_for.label: is irrelevant for

It indicates that the subject does not contribute meaningfully to the context or objectives associated with the object, suggesting a lack of relevance or connection between the two.

Predicate-are_linked_by.label: are linked by
Predicate-are_linked_by.description: The predicate 'are linked by' indicates a relationship of connection or association between the subject and the object, suggesting that the subject is connected to the object through a specific means or method. This connection can imply a variety of forms, such as physical, conceptual, or functional links, and highlights the nature of the relationship that binds the two together.

Predicate-is_used_at.label: is used at
Predicate-is_used_at.description: The predicate 'is used at' establishes a contextual relationship between the subject and the object, indicating the specific setting, level, or domain in which the subject is applicable or relevant. It connects the subject to a particular aspect or category, suggesting that the subject operates or is relevant within the confines of the object.

Predicate-are_used_in.label: are used in
Predicate-are_used_in.description: The predicate 'are used in' indicates a functional relationship where the subject serves a purpose or is applied within the context of the object. It signifies that the subject is actively utilized or implemented in the processes, structures, or activities associated with the object.

Predicate-is_somewhat_irrelevant_for.label: is somewhat irrelevant for
Predicate-is_somewhat_irrelevant_for.description: The predicate 'is somewhat irrelevant for' indicates a relationship where the subject does not significantly contribute to or impact the object, suggesting a limited or negligible relevance. It implies that while there may be some connection or context between the two, the subject's influence or importance in relation to the object is minimal, and the object may proceed independently of the subject.

Predicate-is_looking_at.label: is looking at
Predicate-is_looking_at.description: The predicate 'is looking at' indicates a relationship where the subject is actively observing, examining, or focusing attention on the object. This connection implies a cognitive or perceptual engagement, suggesting that the subject is processing or considering the information or elements represented by the object.

Predicate-are_similar_to.label: are similar to
Predicate-are_similar_to.description: The predicate 'are similar to' establishes a comparative relationship between the subject and the object, indicating that they share common characteristics, features, or attributes. This connection suggests a degree of resemblance or likeness, allowing for the identification of parallels or analogies between the two entities.

Predicate-have_been_introduced_to.label: have been introduced to
Predicate-have_been_introduced_to.description: The predicate 'have been introduced to' indicates a relationship where the subject has encountered or been made aware of the object, typically involving a process of learning or familiarization. It suggests that the subject has gained knowledge or understanding about the object, which can be a concept, system, or entity.

Predicate-conflates.label: conflates
Predicate-conflates.description: The predicate 'conflates' indicates a relationship where the subject merges or combines distinct concepts, ideas, or entities represented by the object, often leading to a blending of their meanings or characteristics. This can imply a lack of clarity or distinction between the two, suggesting that they are treated as if they are the same or closely related, despite potential differences.

Predicate-map_to.label: map to
